On my way back upstairs, I started feeling very weak and dizzy. I stopped at the hall bathroom to use the bathroom. Upon standing up I was feeling incredibly weak and dizzy as if I was about to pass out. I grabbed the sink vanity and the door frame, and the next thing I remember is waking up on the floor with my husband who rushed to my side when he heard the thud of my body hitting the floor. Got back to bed with the help of my husband but felt like I could barely walk I was so weak. Also felt slightly dehydrated. Put a cold compress and ice on my face and rested for the next 6 hours. Will likely have a black eye and suspect I may possibly have broken my nose during my fall. NOTE: I was forced to get this vaccine in order to keep my job; I did not otherwise intend to get the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received dose 1 of the Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot FK5127) at approximately 1115. At 1124, RN approached the patient and mother to inquire about how he felt. The patient reported feeling nauseous. RN transferred patient to zero-gravity chair. PHN and Paramedic approached to assess. At 1125, vital signs: blood pressure 98/72, respirations 12, O2 100%, pulse 96. Patient placed supine. Patient reported improvement in symptoms, no longer nauseous. Patient appeared pale; denied diaphoresis, blurry vision, pain, dizziness. Patient's mother reported he had eaten breakfast and was well hydrated. Patient has no allergies, no medical conditions, and takes gummy vitamins. No history of fainting. Patient reported anxiety to needles. At 1133, PHN offered Benadryl, mother declined. PHN educated patient's mother on remaining for 30min monitoring since report of symptoms, on following up with provider, and ER precautions. Patient sat up and drank water provided by Paramedic. At 1137, vital signs: blood pressure 96/68, pulse 84, O2 100%, respirations 22. Patient reported symptoms had resolved. PHN noted improved skin tone color. At 1140, patient stood up unassisted, continued to report no symptoms. At 1142, patient left with mother, against medical advice of remaining for 30min monitoring from time of reporting symptoms.

She presented to the ED on 9/13 with altered mental status, hypoxia and increased oxygen requirements. Patient was found to be COVID positive despite getting the Pfizer vaccine in January and February of this year. In the ED patient found to have AKI on ESRD, Potassium 6.0, Creatinine 6.09 and BUN 166. She was treated with insulin and dextrose, nephrology was consulted and placed orders for CRRT. Patient was found to have a lactic acidosis (lactate 6.3) and was intubated due to hypoxia and increased work of breathing (continued)  Levo also initiated in the ED after patient received 1L IVF. Started on dexamethasone and remdesivir on 9/13.  Patient went into Afib with RVR and was put on an amiodarone gtt in addition to heparin gtt. Lower respiratory cx grew Proteus and MSSA. Patient was also found to be COVID+. Shock continued to worsen between 9/14 to 9/16 and the patient required Phenylephrine, Giapreza, and Vasopressin in order to maintain her blood pressures with MAP > 60. She required CRRT for AKI with hypotension. Echo showed EF of 70% with elevated RVSP, but fluid could not be pulled consistently with CRRT given her blood pressures. SYMPTOM_TEXT: About midnight, 12 hours after getting the shot, I woke up in the middle of night with severe pain; up and down my spine and back of head - like someone had hit me with sledgehammer. I took Tylenol and that dulled the pain, but I was still in pain. Joints achy and stiff. I kind of expected the achy joints - happened the first two COVID-19 shots. That morning, I tried to get ready for work - got slower and slower in movement and I had a whooshing sound in my ears. I felt very off. When I had woken up, initially, my eyelids hurt but by the time I got going in the morning, there was an intense throbbing behind my eyes. It felt like I was walking through quicksand. Everything (all symptoms) got worse throughout the day. The injection site felt very bruised, and it still does. That's completely normal for me compared with the first doses of the COVID-19 vaccine. There was not redness or swelling this time but just bruised. Yesterday, I got random sharp jabbing pains through various parts of my body; kind of like a shock or a pinched nerve feel. I felt queasy; I had three bouts of diarrhea and a lot of gurgling in my stomach after the diarrhea. From 02:30 - 09:00PM I was "dead to the world," and woke up with intense pain from head to toe. I was disoriented and I thought it was 03:00 in the morning. I texted my daughter to bring the thermometer as I felt chilled and clammy. Fever was 103. 6. My chest was very heavy and tight. I didn't feel like I was wheezing or having trouble breathing but it was concerning to have the heaviness and tightness. I called my primary care doctor. On-call doctor told me to go to ER - since symptoms had worsening it was over 24 hours since vaccine. They tested me for COVID-19 at ER. They gave me Tylenol and IV (Ibuprofen in an IV). And it all dulled the pain, but the pain has still persisted. The fever goes down when I take Tylenol but then it goes back up but only up to 101. It was 99 something this morning but it's 101 around 01:00 or 2:00 today but it's gone back down again. Last night, not moving, my pain was 7 or 8. That was just sitting completely still. If I tried to move the pain was excruciating - it was hard to walk. Right now, the whooshing noise has decreased in my ears; the pain has decreased in joints - still stiff but I can move them. I don't feel so disoriented. They said to come back in tonight if I'm not significantly improved. The pain is still definitely there, and the fever is there but not as bad. They said about 20% of people will have a reaction to this extent for the booster. Blood pressure was significantly low when they took it at ER - 85/58 (my normal reading is 115-120/90). Treatment - stay in bed; Tylenol every six hours. Just before they discharged me this morning, at ER, my hands and feet felt very compressed; like they are being smashed between boards. That was consistent pain for about two hours and when I got home and went to sleep and woke up it wasn't quite as bad. Still stiff though. There's a lot of fatigue. It takes a lot of effort just to have energy to get up and go to the bathroom. I don't feel like I'm passing out, but I just feel like I have to walk slowly to keep my balance because my leg joints and my feet are so stiff that trying to get them to move is a challenge; I haven't felt like I was in danger of collapsing though or that I was going to pass out. The pain was enough to make me cry. I can't believe I'm feeling this bad and that I'm not sick. Two months prior to this, I got the flu vaccine. I think it was on September 2, 2021. Got that at work: set up a flu vaccine site at one of our buildings for Employees. I got that in my right arm which I have never done before.
LAB_DATA: COVID-19; flu - negative Bloodwork - no sign of infection or of any illness going on; they said they were symptoms attributed to booster.  Urine test - no infection found.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 29 year old female patient of Dr. presenting to the office today c/o left arm/shoulder pain x3 weeks. She reports that the pain began immediately while receiving the Flu vaccine in office on 10/12/21. She states that she received the Pneumonia vaccine in the same arm on the same day, which was not painful for her. The Pneumonia shot was given in the lower deltoid and the flu shot was given at the upper deltoid. Patient reports feeling acute pain at the site of injection as the vaccine was being administered. She states that the pain has been constant, has not improved, and is getting worse. It is especially uncomfortable with movement and ADLs, such as: driving, getting dressed, showering, etc. She reports a history of shoulder joint laxity and dislocations in childhood (pt unsure of which shoulder), but states neither shoulder has fully dislocated since middle school when she was playing soccer. She reports that she had extensive PT to both shoulders following the dislocation. She denies experiencing a pain like this in the past, and has not had a similar reaction with previous vaccines. She endorses increased pain with movement and rates it as a 6/10 today. With rest, it is manageable at a 1/10. She denies any bruising, rash, swelling, or pruritis to the injection site/left shoulder. She describes the pain as muscle aches and burning to her left shoulder joint and left arm. She states that it is rare, but occasionally the pain will radiate down to her left wrist. She denies any numbness or tingling in her upper extremities. She denies any recent heavy lifting, strenuous exercise, or falls/trauma. She moved roughly 1 week ago, but states that her mom did the heavy lifting for her d/t discomfort. For pain management, she has been taking 2-3 Advil 200 mg while at work. She states that it helps alleviate some of the pain, but it never completely resolves, just feels more "dull". Patient reports an increase in difficulty sleeping compared to her baseline d/t the pain when she rolls over onto the left side. Of note, she does have a history of narcolepsy, and states that sleep has always been a little tough for her.
OTHER_MEDS: modafinil, ibuprofen, benzaclin gel, atenolol, ascorbic acid.

Her doctor was notified and ordered to start giving Benadryl 25 mg po every 6 hrs. until hives are gone and Tylenol po too.    Recently she was treated for UTI with Augmentin from 10/20/21 ? 10/27/21.   On 10/28/2021 morning, the rash did not get any better. Her vital sign was stable, no fever, O2 sat stable, not in any respiratory distress. Gave Claritin PRN orders with Tylenol at 9AM . RN was called and informed about the patient's condition and to relay message to her doctor.   12:20pm the rash become more worst and spread more to the face and eyes were slightly swollen.   Called RN that we will bring the patient to emergency department at the Hospital for further management and to avoid anaphylactic response.    Arrived at the hospital around 1:20 pm. The ED was fully packed and they were very busy during that time. Some of the patients have to wait outside. Luckily, we were able to get in on time at the waiting area. We waited for a long time to be seen by MD not until almost 5 pm.  She was treated with Decadon 6 mg IM and was also given Vistaril 25 mg PO. The patient was discharged at 7:25 pm and arrived home at 7:40Ppm. Her doctor was called and informed about the patient's condition status. She told me to watch her and check on her in a few minutes, which I did. She said she thought she was going to pass out and her speech was not clear. Since she was getting worse, I called a technician out to help keep her steady and called 911. During the time it took for them to get there, she started shaking slightly and told me she thought she might vomit. She never ended up fainting or throwing up. The paramedics arrived and they took over. She refused the ambulance and had a friend pick her up shortly after, once she was feeling better. She was thankful for our help.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After my vaccine there was just a little tenderness for a few days and about 10 days later I woke up and there was this red circle on my arm and did a Teladoc visit and they told me it was a reaction to the vaccine and then I developed on my collar bone this painful knot and I ended up going to the ER for that and they concluded it was related to the vaccine and my lymph nodes were reacting to it. I still have the nodule but it's no longer a painful nodule and not as big as it was. Then things were okay until July when I had taken a driving trip and back and when I returned I wasn't feeling quite well, and in about 3-4 days my leg started cramping and I thought it was a pulled muscle because of the drive and 3 days after that my calve was swollen and you could physically see the green mark and that's the day (July 15) that I was diagnosed with a DVT and I was kept in the ER overnight and given blood thinners and when I was discharged I had a prescription of Xarelto medication and in the beginning of August I went back to the DR for clearance and she readmitted me to get a full exam and the blood clot was completely gone. So, in a matter of 1 month, I had developed a blood clot, took medications for it, and it was completely gone by August 4 or 5th. I had coughing fits as well in the beginning and every now and again I will have it and my Teladoc wants me to get tested for COVID-19 because it's more often and I have shortness of breath doing things that I normally have energy for. They kept me overnight again in the ER. I did have fatigue and that just kicked in last week and I've been struggling ever since probably Thursday or Friday last week and when I did a Teladoc visit on Monday she wanted me to go straight to the ER, but I can't keep taking time off work. I did take 1/2 a day off today to try and get everything situated before I go to the ER and get tested for COVID-19. When I got diagnosed with my DVT Dr. thinks it was from the drive, but this drive wasn't new to me and I don't think that's what it was from, and the ER nurse thought it was from the vaccine. Around the same time of trop (first part of July) I was supposed to start my cycle and 2-3 days later I started cramping like it was about to start over and it was gut wrenching cramps I've never had before. The Teladoc told me to go t ER again because she thought I was pregnant and had a tubal pregnancy, so I went to the ER, and I had every type of ultrasound possible and wasn't pregnant. They couldn't find out why I was having these issues. 4 days before I ended up in the ER for DVT at this time I had uterine bleeding and I thought I had a pulled muscle, so I didn't mention it to the ER staff. Right now, I'm dealing with the breathing difficulties, shortness of breath, coughing fits, and fatigue. With the fatigue I haven't regained my full energy back since. My mind also feels clouded, and I feel like I'm struggling at work because I can't remember certain things and my mom told me to go straight home but that's been since the vaccine. I'm normally OCD and I remember things very well and I've been struggling really badly.
LAB_DATA: Blood Clot Test Ultrasound Blood Work

I had fatigue, sore ears that were red, and hot, light fever 100.2 degrees, body aches, all over my body-muscles and joints. Under my arm pit area, I had severe pain, like I had marbles under there. The doctor told me it was lymph nodes reacting to the vaccine. Every movement that I made hurt. Itchy on vaccine area and sore and red rash around the injection area. Patient was very nervous about getting the covid Janssen vaccine and worked himself into an anxious state prior to getting injected.  Very soon after getting injected, possibly 5 minutes, he passed out while sitting upright in a chair in the pharmacy.  He quickly, possibly 10 seconds, regained consciousness, at which point we called for EMS.  He was given water, but soon after, possibly 5 minutes, he passed out again.  This time I noticed he was very sweaty and red in the face.  He regained consciousness easily as before, but I insisted he lay down on the floor this time.  With the help of a couple other people, I lowered him gently to the floor, putting a sweatshirt under his head, and feet up on a chair, to raise above his heart.  His color quickly returned to normal and he seemed very alert at this point.  EMS arrived, they evaluated him, and determined he was fine.  After about 15 minutes, he sat back into the chair, drank water, waited another 20 or so minutes, then chose to drive home.  I requested he call when he got home, he did, without any further incident.
Patient vaccinated on 4/10/2021 with Janssen. Requested Janseen for 2nd booster dose. Received Pfizer dose instead.
HISTORY: HTN, GERD, PTSD, MDD, Borderline personality, anxiety, opioid dependence, Suicidal ideation, OSA, primary insomnia

Patient and her husband came in and each wanted a flu shot and a shingles shot. We went through the screening process and the patients went to the immunization area. I came to go over their questionnaires and reconstituted the shingrix for both patients. While this was happening, I was being interrupted with questions and being notified that other patients were waiting in the pharmacy for immunizations and prescriptions. I took the vaccines to the immunization area and the patient was asking me questions. I realized after administering the vaccine in her right arm that I had accidentally administered a second shingrix instead of a Fluad. I apologized to the patient and asked her to wait at least 30 minutes so I could monitor for adverse reactions. The patient was feeling fine and seemed understanding and amicable when she left. I called the manufacturer and they said that the patient would still need a second dose in 2 to 6 months since the second dose was administered less than 4 weeks after the first. I told the patient I would check on her that evening and the next day. She did not answer the phone Friday evening. I will follow up the next day. Patient has not yet exhibited any adverse effects but an administration error did occur.

I received the J & J vaccine in March 2021.  A few weeks later I began to have sharp pain  in my gums when using a water flosser.  I have been using a water flosser for many years without  any adverse side effects. .  I also noticed that my gums were sloughing skin on the right  side of my mouth.  I brushed it off as  having burned my mouth. As I had been healthy my  entire life, I treated this oral pain with OTC medication and stopped using the water flosser.   I assumed that this would heal on its own and did not really worry about it.   But a few weeks   later the sloughing moved to the left side of my mouth.  In August I finally managed to get  an appointment with my dentist.  He said he did not know what was causing this issue and told me to see a periodontist.  I saw a periodontist on Aug 30 who said I had Lichen Planus infection, and he performed a biopsy to verify.  On Sept 22 he called me with the results of the biopsy, diagnosing Mucous Membrane Pemphigoid.  My primary care physician told me to see  an ophthalmologist and a dermatologist.  The dermatologist took a biopsy with the same results.  As of now the only symptoms are oral.  This is a rare auto immune disease that is chronic and progressive. Below is information I got  Mucous Membrane Pemphigoid  General Discussion Mucous membrane pemphigoid (MMP) is a group of rare chronic autoimmune disorders characterized by blistering lesions that primarily affect the various mucous membranes of the body. The mucous membranes of the mouth and eyes are most often affected. The mucous membranes of the nose, throat, genitalia, and anus may also be affected. The symptoms of MMP vary among affected individuals depending upon the specific site(s) involved and the progression of the disease. Blistering lesions eventually heal, sometimes with scarring. Progressive scarring may potentially lead to serious complications affecting the eyes and throat. In some cases, blistering lesions also form on the skin, especially in the head and neck area. The exact cause of MMP is unknown.  MMP has been known by many different names within the medical literature including benign mucous membrane pemphigoid, cicatricial (scarring) pemphigoid, and ocular cicatricial pemphigoid. In March of 2002, a consensus group of researchers determined that mucous membrane pemphigoid was the best designation for this group of disorders. The term "benign" mucous membrane pemphigoid was deemed inappropriate because of the potential for serious complications in some cases. The term "cicatricial" pemphigoid excluded affected individuals who do not develop scarring. Site-specific terms such as "ocular" cicatricial pemphigoid excluded individuals with multiple site involvement.  Signs & Symptoms MMP is characterized by the development of recurring blistering skin lesions affecting the mucous membranes of the body. These lesions may result in scarring of the affected area. Specific symptoms and severity vary from person to person depending upon the specific site(s) involved. It is important to note that affected individuals, in most cases, will not have all of the symptoms listed below.  The mucous membranes lining the mouth and eyes are most commonly affected. In some cases, the first sign of MMP is a red and blistered mouth. The gums (gingivae), roof of the mouth (palate), and the mucous membrane lining the inner cheek (buccal mucosa) may be affected. Involvement of the gums usually results in very red, tender gums that bleed easily and tend to slough off in shreds or sheets. Blistering lesions may spread to affect the tube that carries food from the mouth to the stomach (esophagus) as well as the voice box (larynx) potentially resulting in difficulty swallowing (dysphagia) and hoarseness. After these lesions heal, progressive scarring may occur, resulting in serious complications including narrowing (stenosis) of the esophagus and/or the larynx. In addition, the opening between the vocal cords (supraglottic region) may also narrow (supraglottic stenosis). In rare severe cases, such symptoms can ultimately result in life-threatening complications such as asphyxiation (breathing is cut off).  In many cases of MMP, the mucous membranes lining the eyes (conjunctiva) may be involved. Inflammation of conjunctiva (conjunctivitis) or erosions forming on the conjunctiva may be the initial signs of ocular involvement in MMP. Involvement of the eyes may not be obvious at first, however, and only a special examination by an eye doctor (ophthalmologist) can detect the earliest scarring that develops just beneath the conjunctiva. In most cases, one eye is involved first and the second eye becomes involved later, usually with two years. Ocular symptoms may include pain or grittiness of the eye, increased pressure within the eye (glaucoma), abnormal inward turning of the eyelid (entropion), and abnormal inward turning of the eyelashes (trichiasis) potentially causing irritation of the eyeball. Adhesions may form between the eyelids (symblepharon) or between the eyelid and the eye itself. In some cases, MMP may progress to cause clouding (opacity) of the corneas, loss of vision and, potentially, blindness.  In some cases, affected individuals may develop blistering lesions affecting only the eyes or the mouth, with no involvement of other mucosal sites. Scarring occurs with less frequency in cases of MMP that only involve the mucous membranes of the mouth (oral mucosa). Additional sites where lesions may form include mucous membranes of the nose, genitalia, and anus. Pain, bleeding and scarring may occur at these sites. Urinary and sexual dysfunction may result secondary to genital involvement.  In approximately 20-30 percent of cases, the skin may become involved. In these patients, the skin of the head and neck is usually affected. Skin lesions may be either fluid-filled blisters (bullous) or reddish (erythematous) plaques, which may bleed or itch. Eventually they scar upon healing. Scarring may result in areas of discoloration of the skin (known as hyperpigmentation when it is darkened patches and hypopigmentation when it is light patches). Involvement of the scalp may lead to patchy areas of hair loss (alopecia).  MMP usually has a long duration with frequent remissions and recurrence.  Causes The exact cause of mucous membrane pemphigoid is unknown. MMP is an autoimmune disorder. Autoimmune disorders are caused when the body's natural defenses (antibodies or immunoglobulins) against "foreign" or invading organisms (antigens) begin to attack healthy tissue for unknown reasons. The term autoantibody is used to describe antibodies that are created to attack healthy tissue. The term autoantigen ("self" antigen) is used to describe the normal tissues and cells of the body that are targeted by the autoantibodies.  In patients who have MMP, autoantibodies are being produced that attack the basement membrane zone (BMZ) of the epithelium. The BMZ can be thought of as a sort of "glue" that holds the outer layer of skin (epidermis or oral epithelium) onto the underlying tissues. Once this glue is attacked and destroyed by the autoantibodies, the skin is no longer tacked down, allowing it to lift off and produce blisters.  Researchers believe that in some cases affected individuals may have a genetic susceptibility to developing some forms of MMP. In these cases several factors may contribute to the development of the disorder including immunological, genetic, environmental, and/or other factors. !!!!!!NOT ONE SINGLE PERSON IN MY GENETIC HISTORY, NEITHER MATERNAL OR PATERNAL HAS BEEN DIAGNOSED WITH AN AUTO IMMUNE DISEASE!!!!!!  In a very small number of patients, MMP may be caused by the use of certain prescription drugs. Skin lesions associated with some cases of MMP may appear following trauma to the affected area. Some cases of MMP affecting the eyes may become apparent after eye (ocular) surgery such as cataract removal.  Affected Populations Mucous membrane pemphigoid is a rare group of autoimmune blistering disorders that affects females twice as often as males. The average age of onset of MMP is during the seventh decade (60 to 70 years of age). However, the disorder can occur at any age. The exact incidence of MMP is unknown. Because the disorder is difficult to identify, many researchers believe it is under-diagnosed.  AS  UP CAN SEE, THIS IS A SERIOUS DISEASE WITH DEVESTATING SYMPTOMS. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Adverse Reaction: The next day after receiving the vaccine, I woke up with terrible body aches and fatigue like a had the flu. Over the next week, on my right side, my scalp became hypersensitive, and numbness crept down my neck, shoulder and right arm. In the second and third weeks, my arm became weak and uncoordinated to the point where I could not hold things or do much with my right, dominant arm. I additionally felt weak, fatigued and had terrible restless legs. During the fourth week after the vaccine, I began to lose balance and could not stand without holding onto something. I also lost strength and coordination in my right leg. My gait was not normal, and I could only take small steps. I was so fatigued that I could hardly do anything for myself. My body was completely weak, and my right side was partially paralyzed.  Treatment: After initially seeing a doctor, I was immediately sent to a neurologist, and I remain under care of a neurologist to this day. An MRI was performed on July 6, 2011 which revealed transverse myelitis. I was given a five-day 1000 mg treatment of IV steroids (methylprednisone). I elected to do this out-patient due to cost and family at home. I then did physical therapy over the next six months.  Outcome: The steroid treatment did not improve symptoms but did stop further progression. With time and therapy, I have regained sensation that was lost. Strength has improved on my right side but remains weak, and my gait is not always normal. In 2016, I was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis.
LAB_DATA: July 6, 2011 - MRI with contrast Lab work Spinal tap Result: Transverse Myelitis

negative IgG titers to diphtheria and Haemophilus influenza type B vaccine/ patient has immune dysfunction/did not result in any functional IgG production again pneumococcus; This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published literature article, titled as stated below and refers to a female patient of unknown age. The patient was born via donor embryo to a 46-year-old woman, who had been diagnosed with pre�B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia during her 18th week of pregnancy. The mother received 3 cycles of chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, dexamethasone, and 5 cycles of rituximab. A bone marrow biopsy at 21 weeks gestation demonstrated leukemia remission. The last chemotherapy cycle was completed by 28 weeks, the last dose of rituximab was completed at 27 weeks. The mother had complete blood count recovery before the planned cesarean section at 30 weeks gestational age. The newborn patient had a relatively uncomplicated neonatal intensive care unit course, she did not require intubation or ventilator support, and was able to be discharged by 7 weeks of life. The infant did not receive maternal breast milk to minimize any potential for further rituximab exposure. Her complete blood count (CBC) at delivery was within normal limits: white blood cell count 12.1�10^3/mcL, absolute lymphocyte count (ALC) was 1600/mcL (normal 29 to 31 weeks gestational age ALC: 3219/mcL [800 to 5800]), absolute neutrophil count (ANC) 9922/mcL (normal 29 to 31 wk gestational age ANC: 12000/mcL [7800 to 14500]), hemoglobin 11.4 g/dL, and platelets 447�10^3/mcL. Despite this severe lymphopenia, a repeat CBC on day of life 2 revealed improved ALC of 2530 mcL. She received 1 red blood cell transfusion for a drop in hemoglobin to 9.8 g/dL at day 3 of life. The infant had 2 normal newborn screens.   On unknown dates, she was vaccinated with haemophilus b conjugate vaccine (meningococcal protein conjugate)(manufacturer unknown) and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis (dose #, exact doses, routes, anatomical locations, lot # and expiration dates were not reported). Other vaccines included: tetanus, hepatitis B, polio strain 1 and diphtheria.  At 10 weeks of life during a scheduled follow-up, the patient was found to be severely neutropenic with an ANC of 0 in addition to severe hypogammaglobulinemia with immunoglobulin (Ig)G of 62mg/dL (normal: 206 to 601; 95% confidence interval, for age 2mo). Because of fever following her 2 months immunizations, the patient was admitted and was treated with intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG)�2 doses which resulted in the improvement of her ANC to 528. A neutrophil antibody screening test was not done at this time but based on improvement of ANC following IVIG infusion. With concern for recurrent neutropenia, the decision was made to give her intermittent granulocyte colony stimulation factor 5mcg/kg with gradual return of her ANC to normal levels without granulocyte colony stimulation factor by 9 months of age, where it has remained. However, the patient has continued to have severe hypogammaglobulinemia requiring IVIG every 4 to 8 weeks to maintain IgG> 400 mg/dL. At 10 months of life she demonstrated improvement in IgM levels but continued to have a severe deficiency in IgG and IgA. Lymphocyte subset analysis by flow cytometry at 10 and 15 months of age demonstrated a grossly normal number of B cells: 1410 and 1797 cells/�L, respectfully (normal range of 600 to 2700 cells/�L); her IgM levels were close to normal at 10 months (patient: 30 mg/dL, normal 82 mg/dL (41 to 149 mg/dL) and in the normal range at 15 months of age (patient: 61 mg/dL, normal 93 mg/dL [43 to 173 mg/dL]); however, she remains profoundly deficient in IgG with nadirs below 300. At 19 months of age, further evaluation by flow cytometry revealed this B-cell population consisted of IgM-only memory B cells, with no evidence of the next stage in development of the B cell to an IgG antibody secreting, class switched B cell. Repeat B-cell phenotyping at 24 months of age continued to demonstrate a complete absence of class switched B cells and the patient remains on IVIG infusions to maintain IgG levels >400 mg/dL. The patient is currently 4 years of age. Attempts at weaning off the IVIG have failed thus far. Spacing IVIG to 6-week intervals (~2 half lifes) resulted in IgG levels <300 mg/dL (normal, 728 mg/dL [441 to 1135 mg/dL]) and a recurrent stye. Given her frequent IVIG infusions, it is difficult to interpret vaccine response, the patient has demonstrated variable response to protein antigen vaccines. She had potential positive response to tetanus, hepatitis B, polio strain 1 vaccines, with unknown longevity of the response. She had negative IgG titers to diphtheria and Haemophilus influenza type B vaccine suggesting that positive antibody titers to other vaccines may not be real. Remarkably, the patient has had few infections despite her immunologic dysfunction. The outcome of the event was unknown. Multiple attempts at giving the patient other vaccines such as pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine combined with spreading IVIG out up to 3 months did not result in any functional IgG production again pneumococcus suggesting continued immune dysregulation in this patient.  The reporter considered the event to be related to suspect vaccines.   A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up in the middle of the night 23 days after my second dose of the Pfizer covid vaccine with intense chest pain like I have never felt before. Nothing I did would lessen it (moving, ice, drinking water, etc). Eventually, I went back to sleep until I went to urgent care the next day where they said costochondritis and prescribed rest and ibuprofen. This did not help at all and the pain was consistently there for the next week. Then the tingles started. I first felt it in the back of my arms, then my legs, soon my face, and then all over my chest. My thumbs went numb intermittently. These symptoms appeared seemingly at random throughout my day for weeks at varying levels of intensity. They could come suddenly and then persist from anywhere from 20 minutes to hours. Then they would fade and a different part of my body begin to tingle. All while having a now dull chest pain constantly. Several times I would wake up in the middle of the night tingling all over and would not be able to go back to sleep - it was terrifying to feel like your body is attacking itself. Over the course of several months, I had extensive blood work done, an EKG heart stress test, and an MRI of my brain and spine along with numerous phone and in-person appointments with multiple general practitioners, specialists, physical therapists, and a psychologist.  ALL of them said everything looked fine and on paper, I am perfectly healthy with no explanation for my symptoms. Eventually, after months, the symptoms began to fade. The tingling left first and then the chest pain - although I do occasionally still feel it but much less intense. It is like waves come and go with each wave lasting less time and being less intense. I can only hope that eventually it will go away and I will not feel like this anymore. I have no underlying health conditions and am a healthy 34-year-old woman at a healthy weight.
LAB_DATA: 4/14/21 - Urgent Care - diagnosed costochondritis    5/3/2021 - Telephone Appointment Visit - ordered lab tests - review continued pain   5/8/2021 - Telephone Appointment Visit - ordered more lab tests, neurology consult and heart test - reviewed last tests and continued pain   5/12/2021 - Office Visit with Neurology - physical assessment was normal - ordered MRI of brain and spinal cord (tests came back normal with slight disc bulge which primary care and neurologist said would not cause tingling I was having)   5/20/21- EKG Heart Stress Test - results came back normal   6/9/21 - Telephone Appointment Visit - discussed results and continued pain    6/15/21 - Telephone Appointment Visit - discussed continued pain - ordered physical therapy    6/23/21 - Office Visit - discussed continued pain, ordered more blood tests and psychologist consutlt    6/25/21 - Video Visit with Psychiatrist - discussed stress management and symptoms, discussed no need for medication and symptoms do not seem stress-related    7/6/21 - Physical Therapist Appointment - discussed pain and exercises given    7/29/21 - Physical Therapist Appointment - discussed pain and exercises given    8/12/21-  Office Visit with Spinal Specialist - diagnosed as normal based on looking at x-rays, MRI and physical assessment
OTHER_MEDS: Smarty Pants Prenatal Vitamin (for nursing at the time)

It was reported that Patient reports that he was diagnosed with Pericarditis and AFib 8 days after receiving the second shot on 11March2021 in his deltoid. Patient stated that on 19March2021 went to the ER with chest pain. They tested him and discharged him. On 21March2021, patient had chills, felt weak, had low energy, and on 22March2021 he had chest pain that patient didn't like so was then hospitalized. Patient had shortness of breath. Diagnosed with Pericarditis and Atrial Fibrillation. Had chest pain, Shortness of breath upon exertion (walking, going up the stairs he needs to stop and catch his breath), terrible cough. Patient had chest pain, low energy, chills, felt weak, terrible cough, shortness of breath upon exertion, high blood sugar, terrible cough. He almost passed out several times from the bad coughs.  This case concerns a 79-year-old, male patient with previous relevant medical history of stent placement, who experienced the unexpected events of atrial fibrillation and pericarditis. Company comment: This is Spontaneous case concerning a 64-year-old, male patient with unknown medical history, who experienced the unexpected serious (medically significant) events of insomnia and impaired work ability along other non serious events. The events occurred approximately 2 months after the second dose of Spikevax. Patient presented with vaccination site pain which impacted on his sleep ability, but this difficulty continued so he was prescribed multiple drugs for insomnia, trazondone, clonazepam, alprazolam, venlafaxine and eszopiclone. The event is ongoing (over a month) and resistant to these multiple drugs. This has impacted on his work ability. The rechallenge is not applicable. These events are considered medically significant based on duration, drug resistance and significant disability on work activities. The benefit-risk relationship of Spikevax is not affected by this report. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a literature report from the Annals of Allergy, Asthma, & Immunology, 2021, vol 127 (4); pp 498-499; DOI 10.1016/j.anai.2021.07.020 entitled Biphasic anaphylaxis after first dose of messenger RNA coronavirus disease 2019 vaccine with positive polysorbate 80 skin testing result.  Initial reports of anaphylaxis after the first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech (Pfizer Inc, vaccine suggested a case rate of 11.1 per million doses, but subsequent reports estimate a rate of 5 per million doses). In a recent description of 21 anaphylaxis cases after the first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine, there were no biphasic reactions. We present the case of an individual who experienced suspected biphasic anaphylaxis after the first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) vaccine.  A 42-year-old female nurse with depression and anxiety treated with bupropion but no previous atopic history or anaphylaxis presented for her first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine at a nurse and paramedic staffed employee vaccination clinic in a major hospital. After 10 minutes from vaccination, she developed facial angioedema noted by multiple medical providers, sensation of throat closure, hoarse voice, and a pruritic rash on her neck and upper chest with no substantial injection site reaction. At the vaccination site, she was treated with oral diphenhydramine and 0.3 mg intramuscular epinephrine with symptom improvement. She was transported to the emergency department, where she had a heart rate of 108 bpm and blood pressure of 137/87 mm Hg. She was treated with 20 mg intravenous famotidine and 10 mg intravenous dexamethasone and observed for 6 hours without symptom recurrence. A tryptase drawn 90 minutes after symptom onset was elevated at 12.5 ng/mL (<11.5 ng/mL). She was discharged with an epinephrine autoinjector and initially did well, but the following evening (30 hours postvaccination), she developed recurrent tongue swelling (noted by husband), sensation of throat closing, eye puffiness, diaphoresis, and lightheadedness. She administered oral diphenhydramine and her epinephrine autoinjector with rapid improvement in her symptoms. She went back to the emergency department where providers noted resolution of tongue swelling but persistent periorbital edema. There was no rash. Her heart rate was 109 bpm, and her blood pressure was 121/ 74 mm Hg. She was treated with 10 mg intravenous dexamethasone, observed for 4 hours, and discharged with no subsequent symptom recurrence. She was evaluated in an allergy clinic 3 weeks after her reaction. Further history revealed previous tolerance of polyethylene glycol (PEG)-containing medications (MiraLAX). She had no known drug allergies or dermal fillers. Because of her marked systemic reaction, she underwent expanded skin testing.4 Testing results to PEG, methylprednisolone sodium, methylprednisolone acetate, and polysorbate 20 were negative. Skin testing result to triamcinolone acetonide (containing polysorbate 80) was negative with a 40 mg/mL skin prick and 1:100 and 1:10 intradermals but result to a 1:1 intradermal was positive (Table 1). Additional testing results were positive to Refresh sterile eye drops (Allergan), negative to Prevnar-13 (both containing polysorbate 80), and negative to the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine (Table 1). A baseline serum tryptase was persistently elevated at 12.8 ng/mL, although spot urine measurements of mast cell mediators (leukotriene E4, 2,3-dinor-11beta-prostaglandin F2 alpha, and N-methylhistamine) were normal. KIT D816V mutation testing result on peripheral blood was negative but testing result for hereditary alpha tryptasemia was positive with an extra alpha tryptase copy number. She is avoiding the second dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine until an in-office challenge is performed. Several aspects of this case deserve discussion. Biphasic anaphylaxis is well described but uncommon, occurring in approximately 3% of adults who develop anaphylaxis. Risk factors for a biphasic reaction include previous anaphylaxis, unknown trigger, and delayed epinephrine administration, although these are variable among different study populations. In adults, the estimated median time from exposure to the biphasic reaction is 15 hours. Our case is unique in the fact that the patient had a biphasic reaction despite no history of allergy and prompt receipt of epinephrine during the initial reaction, although some symptoms may have been anxiety related. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first reported case of suspected biphasic anaphylaxis to the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine. Another interesting aspect is the positive polysorbate 80 skin test result. Polysorbate 80 is a large nonionic compound that is a widely used excipient in many oral and injectable medications, including the Janssen COVID-19 vaccine, but is not present in the messenger RNA (mRNA) COVID-19 vaccines. It is cross-reactive with PEG, another excipient thought to be the leading culprit in allergic reactions to the mRNA COVID-19 vaccines. Immunoglobulin E and non-immunoglobulin E-mediated mechanisms are implicated in polysorbate and PEG reactions. Expert opinion suggests an algorithm using nonirritating concentrations for PEG and polysorbate testing in the evaluation of patients with possible anaphylaxis to the mRNA COVID-19 vaccines. There has only been 1 report of immediate hypersensitivity from a polysorbate 80-containing vaccine (Gardasil) with positive results to skin prick and intradermal testing to this vaccine 8. It is plausible that our patient's reaction to the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine was the result of PEG and polysorbate 80 cross-reactivity, which has been previously reported, albeit in patients with a positive PEG skin testing result. Our patient's negative results to PEG and methylprednisolone skin tests may suggest against cross-reactivity, although an alternative explanation is that the PEG concentration used for skin testing was too low to elicit a positive reaction. Owing to institutional restrictions, intradermal testing to the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine was unable to be performed, which would be the next step in evaluation. In addition, use of Refresh is non-standardized and based on expert opinion without established nonirritating concentrations. The sensitivity and specificity of skin testing to the vaccine and its components are unknown as is the mechanism of reaction. More patients will have to be evaluated to elucidate this further. A final interesting point is the patient's persistent tryptase elevation 3 weeks after her index reaction. Systemic mastocytosis and monoclonal mast cell activation syndrome were deemed less likely after her negative KIT mutation testing result. Nevertheless, genetic testing result for hereditary alpha tryptasemia was positive and may have contributed to her symptoms given its association with elevated basal serum tryptase and increased risk of severe anaphylaxis. Despite this case report, in the overwhelming majority of cases, the risk of morbidity and mortality from COVID-19 will far outweigh the risk associated with vaccination. Although more study is needed to determine the use of skin testing in the evaluation of vaccine reactions, the widespread vaccination of the global population is imperative in the control of the pandemic.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information in the case, a contributory effect of the vaccine BNT162B2 to the reported events cannot be ruled out. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

Discomfort in right lower back; Spasms-not external muscles but internal/Spasms become very rapid/ Spasms and pain moved up back to waist then moved to front, and continued up abdominal area stopping at rib cage; Shooting staightline pain from right of spinal chord horizontally across back and spasming area; Shooting staightline pain from right of spinal chord horizontally across back and spasming area; Shooting staightline pain from right of spinal chord horizontally across back and spasming area/ Spasms and pain moved up back to waist; Spasms and pain moved up back to waist, then moved to front, and continued up abdominal area stopping at rib cage; Spasms and pain moved up back to waist, then moved to front, and continued up abdominal area stopping at rib cage; Spasms and pain moved up back to waist, then moved to front, and continued up abdominal area stopping at rib cage; Cyst on ovary; This spontaneous case from the United States was retrieved on 04-Oct-2021 from Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) (reference number: 1685020-1), reported by other non-health professional (consumer) and concerned a 75-year-old, female patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included hypertension (HTN), atrial fibrillation (A-fib), familial essential tremors, cephalosporins, penicillin, statins, citrus, shellfish and metal allergies. The patient's concomitant medications included losartan, furosemide, potassium chloride (reported as ''KCl''), metoprolol, buspirone, vitamin B complex (vit b complex), cinnamon (cinnamomum verum), lorazepam and Eliquis (apixaban), all used for an unreported indications. The patient had regular influenza shots, annually for many years with no problems.  On 22-Oct-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59; dose reported as one, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: right arm; indication: not reported). The batch number reported was 279813.  On the same day, within ten seconds after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient felt discomfort in right lower back, which quickly became more severe with spasms which were not external muscles but internal. Spasms became very rapid and severe with shooting staightline pain from right of spinal cord (reported as ''spinal chord''), horizontally across back and spasming area. Spasms and pain moved up back to waist, then moved to front, and continued up abdominal area stopping at rib cage. The patient went to emergency department (ED). Upon arrival, spasms and pain continued subsiding after about 45 minutes. Electrocardiogram (EKG) was performed and the patient was monitored for vitals, with no unusual result and computerised tomogram (CT) abdomen revealed nothing unusual except for cyst on ovary. The patient did not receive any medications in ED and was discharged with no further events. Additionally, the patient visited physician's office and her doctor recommended no more quadrivalent.   On the same day, the patient recovered from all events, except from the event of 'cystic ovary' for which the outcome was not reported.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.   The case was assessed as non-serious.  Company comment: A 75-year-old patient developed back discomfort, muscle and abdominal spasms, as well as spinal, back, rib and abdominal pain on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product Fluad Quadrivalent. Advanced age of patient confounds causality. Computerised tomogram of abdomen revealed nothing unusual except for cyst on ovary. Causality for the reported ovarian cyst is assessed as not related due to biological implausibility. Due to suggestive chronology, causality is assessed as possibly related for all other events.; Sender's Comments: A 75-year-old patient developed back discomfort, muscle and abdominal spasms, as well as spinal, back, rib and abdominal pain on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product Fluad Quadrivalent. I laid down around 9:30 on the night of 11/03 with shortness of breath and very mild chest pain. It got progressively worse over the course of the next 3 hours, to the point that I decided to go to the ER. Hospital performed a chest x-ray, EKG, blood tests (CBC & D-dimer were 2 I'm aware of), and CT scan. Apparently my D-dimer was elevated, so they performed CT scan, which ruled out a pulmonary embolism. The doctor informed me it might have been a reaction to the vaccine, but was unable to determine the cause. I was discharged from the Hospital around 7:00AM on 11/04.  The chest pain subsided, but the shortness of breath has persisted since.   I'm still experiencing shortness of breath, but not to the same degree. Also, I will occasionally feel a mild tingling sensation in my hands and feet.

First shot: 09/22/21: (At different pharmacy):  Intermittent nonexertional nonpleuritis 2/10 Left sided chest pain started roughly 9 hrs after vaccine shot and lasted for roughly 20 hours  Second Shot: 10/21/21 (At pharmacy address provided) : Irregularly irregular heart rate, excessive perspiration, dizziness, confusion first noted roughly 17 hrs after the vaccine shot. Highest heart rate noted was around 135 (not sure exact number). I have a picture of heart rate 128 noted on my pulse ox. There was vasospasm (pain) in different areas of body but no chest pain. Headaches were persistent occasionally generalized but often point ice-pick like headaches. Irregular heart rate worsened with mild exertion like climbing one flight of stairs (Absence of any cardiac personal or family history). When symptoms persisted for 5 days after second shot, I decided to take anti-inflammatories. I took two doses of Ibuprofen. I also took Curcumin (One of natural anti-inflammatories well studied and published). Taking anti-inflammatories for 3 days helped to reduce heart rate irregularities. My heart rate now (Day 17 post second shot) varies between 80-95 beats per minute (my baseline heart rate prior to vaccine was in 60s). I did not have ice-pick headache for last few days. However, generalized mild headache is often noted (last one yesterday evening).  Not sure if I fully recovered from adverse event as my baseline heart rate prior to vaccine first shot was in 60s. Now my Heart rate varies between 80-90s on day 17 after second vaccine shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I recieved the first dose of Moderna shot March 17th.  Got my period March 22nd and had it regular.. medium to light flow and lasting 4 days which is normal and always has been being on birth control. The 2nd shot I got April 14th.  My period was supposed to come the week after and it didn't. I  had the symptoms of cramping the usual but my period didn't come which has never happened. I took a pregnancy test and was not pregnant. The next month in May I got it but for 2 days. It was extremely heavy the first day which has never happened and light the 2nd day and then done. Like I said my normal patterns are 4 days and medium to light every cycle. The next month June, it came and I had it for 10 days. Medium to heavy flow. Again, has never happened and that is odd for that long. July came and I got it for 3 days.. August, I got it for 2 days. September I had it for 3 days. October I got it for 3 days. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented with her brother (who is developmentally disabled) to vaccine clinic today 11/6/21. Both patient and her brother had appointments for booster doses of vaccine. Patient was scheduled for Pfizer booster, and brother was scheduled for Moderna booster. Due to brother's condition, it was necessary for him to remain with patient during their appointments. The seating at the clinic for patients is divided into rows by vaccine type. Because patient and brother needed to remain together, they were both seated in  the "Pfizer row". When approached to begin vaccination encounter, I and my scribe verified patient name and DOB. Scribe then asked the patient if she is here for the Moderna booster and she responded "yes". After preparing the vaccine and cleaning the site, I asked the patient "and you are getting the Moderna booster, correct?" and patient answered "yes". After administering the vaccine patient stated (paraphrasing here) and he is getting the Moderna. This led me to question the administration on the Moderna booster to this patient. I then administered the Moderna booster to patient's brother.  I did not question the patient directly at this time.  All seating is in close proximity to other patients, and I wanted to verify with the second RN in question that the patient had indeed stated yes when asked if she is getting the Moderna booster. I reviewed what had happened with the second RN that was present at the time and he confirmed that patient responded affirmatively when asked if she is receiving the Moderna booster.  Accompanying staff advised me on next steps including contacting the patient to notify her that she has received the Moderna vaccine, filing an incident report, entering report into VAERS. Manager on site was made aware of the situation as well. Patient was called and was notified that she received Moderna booster.

Client received the Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot#FK1527) in the L deltoid and the Fluarix Quadrivalent Influenza Vaccine (Lot#3NA4M) in the R deltoid at approximately 1050 from vaccinator RN. After the client received both vaccines, he stood up to wait next to his mother who was receiving her COVID vaccine from the same vaccinator. Due to a limited supply of chairs at the mobile event there was not an available chair to allow the client to sit down while waiting with his mother. At approximately 1055, as the client was standing next to his mother, he began to slouch over the vaccination table and vaccinator RN's assisted client to the ground. Client lost consciousness for approximately 2 seconds. RN assessed non obstructed airway, no respiratory distress, and raised the client's legs while he was laying on the floor. RN assessed client who presented with mild pallor of the face, no diaphoresis, and pupils equal and reactive. RN took client vitals at 1103 with BP 100/60 in the L arm laying down, 70 HR, and 16 RR. Lead RN assessed client at 1103 presented A&O x4 and talking in full sentences,  grip strong and equal, cap refill < 3 seconds, and skin pink and warm to touch.  Client's mother reported that the client ate breakfast at 0830 and had a muffin. Client denied dizziness, SOB, headache, numbness, or tingling. Client was assisted to zero-gravity chair and Lead RN advised that the client be observed for 30 minutes. Client's father reported that he has a history of fainting but reported that the client has never fainted in the past. Lead RN provided client with water, juice, and graham crackers. Client took sips of the water and juice and ate his snacks. Client reported to Lead RN that he was "feeling good now" and denied any dizziness, SOB, headache, numbness, or tingling. RN reviewed when to f/u with PCP. At 1140 the client left the vaccine site with his parents. Client walked out of the vaccine site with a steady and symmetrical gait.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 10/29/21 Began experiencing calf muscle tightness with shin splint like pains in left leg.  10/30/21 Left ankle became randomly swollen. No physical injury sustained to cause this. Accompanied with spasms of lightning pain (10 on pain scale) in the ankle and lower shin area in left leg. Random pins and needles pains as well. Visited Urgent Care. Doctor, could not determine cause of swelling. Sited no sprain. Performed blood test for clots and found none. Recommended keeping left leg elevated with periodic icing of swollen ankle. Prescribed Naproxen 500MG. Continued to experiencing frequent lightning pain spasms in left leg throughout the day.  10/31/21 Condition worsened throughout the night. Spasms in left leg, ankle and shin area became more frequent with consistent pain level of 10. Contacted Urgent care and informed them of condition. Recommended to visit Emergency Room to perform ultrasound for blood clots. Was taken by mother to Doctor's Emergency Room. Seen by Physician and Practitioner. Ultrasound was performed and no blood clots were detected. Recommended continue taking Naproxen. Was prescribed Cyclobenzaprine (Flexeril) 5MG tabs and Methylprednisolone 4MG tabs. Discharged from the ER same day. Returned home and continued to experience frequent spasms with lightning pain (10). Pain became traveling and would now be experienced in different parts of left leg. Sometimes ankle, sometimes higher up as close as kneecap.  11/01/21 Spasms persisted but with less frequency. Pain level also reduced from a 10 to 6 on scale. Ankle remained slightly swollen.  11/02/21 Spams very infrequent and pain now localized in lower left shin. Ankle remained slightly swollen.   11/03/21 Spasms and pain had stopped. Ankle remained slightly swollen.  11/04/21 Was able to return to work. (Work days missed 10/30/21 through 11/03/21) Ankle slightly swollen, but no excruciating pain. Had a slight limp.  11/05/21 Slight inflammation in ankle, no pain, walking normal.  11/06/21 Very little inflammation in ankle, no pain, walking normal.
LAB_DATA: 10/30/21 Blood work performed at Urgent Care. Negative for blood clots. 10/31/21 Ultrasound performed at Doctor's Hospital. Negative for blood clots.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received dose 1 of the Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot FK5127) at 1212. At 1220, the patient's body went limp and his head slumped forwards while sitting in his father's arms. The patient's father called for help. Patient's mother reported the patient was not responding to verbal stimuli. PHN and PHN approached to assess patient. Patient appeared pale and diaphoretic. Patient started responding to verbal stimuli asking "what's going on?" PHN and father assisted patient to the ground. Vital signs: blood pressure 90/58, O2 99%, pulse 84, respirations 24. At 1225, patient reported he saw black and felt sleepy but currently symptoms improved. Patient's mother reported patient had allergies to ibuprofen and bandage adhesive, no medical conditions, and takes no medication. PHN offered Benadryl but patient's mother declined. PHN educated on remaining for 30min monitoring from time symptoms started, to follow up with provider, and ER precautions. Patient's mother reported that patient had no prior history of syncope. PHN offered patient water and applesauce but patient declined. At 1228, patient reported symptoms had resolved. Vital signs: blood pressure 94/62, O2 99%, pulse 78, respirations 20. At 1245, patient sat up, continued reporting no symptoms. Vital signs: blood pressure 92/60, O2 99%, pulse 80, respirations 18. At 1248, patient stood up, continued reporting no symptoms. Patient left walking with steady gait at 1250 accompanied by parents and sibling.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received 1st dose Pfizer. No history of allergies to food/meds. Received vaccine at 11:27 am and started feeling "funny" while waiting post vaccine. We immediately brought him back into the IMZ room. His anxiety escalated and he felt dizzy like he was going to pass out. We gave him an ice pack for his head. No nausea. He lost all color in his skin. Then his legs began to tingle. BP: 179/83. Pulse: 92. He asked that we call 911. He started to regain color and feel a little better and then it hit him again (another wave of symptoms). Emergency arrived around 11:47 am and took him to the hospital. After speaking with him last evening he said he has been very thirsty all day. His KCl was a little low at the hospital and they gave him an IV. The ER could not determine exactly what happened. They are classifying it as an allergic reaction because some of the symptoms. It could have been the start of anaphylaxis; although no issues with breathing/swelling.
LAB_DATA: ER verified his potassium was low, but I cannot validate what labs/tests were ran.

Stents were from the common iliac artery through the external iliac artery common femoral artery superficial femoral artery into the below-knee popliteal artery. About 12 hours after receiving the 2nd shot of the Pfizer vaccine, I had severe body aches, chills, sweats. I didn?t sleep most of the night. My body temperature reached 99.6 F which is high for me because I tend to be cold. The symptoms continued through the next day 10/30. I was bed ridden the entire day on 10/30. 10/31, I had started to feel better, but also had chest pain that started. After a couple hours, it would go away and come back for a couple hours and then go away. By 11/1, I woke up at 4:00am with severe chest pain. This time it wouldn?t go away like normal. I called my doctor and got in to see her for an appointment at 10:00am. Still the chest pain was there. My temperature was 99.1F by then. I was so fatigued. It was worse than having actual COVID-19 which I had in December 2020. I had an EKG done which came back normal. My doctor wrote me out from work for the week, and I worked from home as I could. I was so exhausted and tired all the time.  By Thursday, 11/5, the chest pain had gone away along with the other symptoms except for fatigue. On Friday, 11/6 left the house to go grocery shopping. After 1 hour, I was exhausted. I came home around 12:00pm and had a migraine headache set in. One of the worst I?ve had in my life. The migraine had lasted the rest of that day and all through 11/7. Around 1:00pm on Friday 11/5 I started my menstrual cycle which was 3 days early for me. It was light and spotty. That?s not normal for me to be early or for it to be just spotty. Around 4:00am I woke up to a extreme menstrual bleeding. I hopped out of bed and blood had soaked through my entire super heavy overnight pad and was running down both sides of my legs. I?ve never had such severe bleeding in my life. My migraine headache had moved to the right side temple of my head and was pounding. Around 9:00am 11/6 I had nausea and the chills all over again like the day right after I had received the 2nd dose. Around 6:00pm, my migraine had subsided. My body aches and chills are gone. I still have extreme bleeding from my cycle, but I?ll see what happens in the days ahead. The fatigue and brain fog is still lingering.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient has a history of metastatic prostate cancer that had been well controlled for nearly a decade after prostatectomy in 2010.  In conjunction with first vaccination dose, PSA was measured reported 2/17/21 at 2.32 ng./mL.  PSA had been measured at 1.72 in 11/18/2020, and 1.80 on 8/19/2020.   Shortly thereafter, patient began to experience significant blood clots and blood in the urine.    CT scan taken 3/12/21 reported growing tumor in prostate region and bladder.  "Multiple new bilateral <8mm solid pulmonary nodules concerning for metastasis,"  and "possible metastatic progression in nodes and ?lungs".  Within 45 days after 2nd shot, patient had multiple ER trips/hospitalizations for gross hematuria, necessitating catheterization and irrigation, as well as clot retention at one admission.  Subsequent cystoscopy confirmed prostate cancer invasion into bladder.    By 6/23/2021, PSA had increased to 2.93 ng/mL, and by 8/18/2021, PSA increased to 6.65 ng/mL.  Constant urinary bleeding.  Patient experienced a-fib, was admitted to hospital for more urinary bleeding.  Patient underwent 20 days of radiation in-hospital to attempt to address the tumor/bleeding.
LAB_DATA: See above.  Chart is 100+ pages long post-February 2021 detailing multiplicity of problems.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received Pfizer vaccine as his tertiary series for COVID-19 vaccination. He arrived with his wife and two sons for vaccination. He received Moderna as the booster. She asked him if he was OK. He replied that he just needed "some fresh air."  He got up to go outside and his wife followed him. I originally received the J&J vaccine in March 2021 and had no side effects. My family is traveling to  in December so my husband and I went to receive our booster shots.  Moderna was available and we went to a local pharmacy  to get that booster The following day I experienced the usual reported side effects - headache, nausea, vomiting/dry heaves, fever (101.4) and chills. Then I started to experience extremely high blood pressure (while I had fainted twice in the previous week because my BP was too low - around 70/50 it was then presenting at 200+/100+),extreme anxiety, uncontrollable shaking (my doctor told me it was called psychogenic movement disorder as a result of extremely high anxiety. If these had been reported side effects, I may not have gone to the emergency room, as at the time I was unemployed.At the time I was admitted my BP was 208/108.
LAB_DATA: Chest xray to see if I had an enlarged heart of if there were blockages; extensive blood work to see if there was, among other things, an issue with my kidney function; an EKG to see if I was having a heart attack and other physical tests to see if I was having a stroke.. They found nothing abnormal and determined that these  symptoms were as a result of the COVID booster.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The expected sore arm occurred following vaccination, which raised no level of concern, except that I have had previous bad reactions to vaccines as a child. A slight fever began roughly around 7pm, again, not a sign of concern. The night of vaccination, however, I awoke with severe body pain my fever fluctuated above 103. I could hardly stand, and my vision was blurred. The body pains went beyond the normal muscle aches and pains that may occur with fever (I have had several cases of pneumonia, and scarlet fever once in my life). This was the most pain I had ever been in, and was an extremely unexpected reaction. I had inflammation/pain in all my joints, and it was most extreme in my lower back/hip area where I have ongoing chronic pain (the cause of this chronic pain is yet undiagnosed). I almost went to the emergency room, but did not have health insurance at the time, and was concerned about the financial burden.  To help with my symptoms, I took an NSAID to help relieve symptoms, but the pain and high fever continued the next few days. Eventually, the symptoms resolved the following week, but not without increased long-term inflammation and pain in my joints, hips, etc. I often experience an elevated body temperature (not quite a fever, though), and I currently take some herbal anti-inflammatories to help with the inflammation. However, this adverse reaction has had a long-term effect on my health.
LAB_DATA: I have had some blood tests completed after I was able to get on insurance in September. Most findings were normal, although I have had left-shifted immature granulocytes. There is a presence of promyelocytes on my CBC differential, in addition to myelocytes and metamyelocytes. I am still awaiting a CRP to examine an intense chest pain I experienced, and am getting an X-ray soon to better understand the hip pain.
PRIOR_VAX: MMR- Age Unsure, Tetanus- Age 12

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 12 hours, could not sleep, had body aches, and loss of strength.  Could not stand up from a seated position by herself.  Condition continued to worsen. She still could not stand or walk on her own and barely with two people helping her at maximum assistance.  On April 2, she was transferred from the rehab facility to the ER by ambulance due to worsening condition and not responsive but heart was fine.  Was transferred back to the rehab facility that night after being treated.  On April 6 was transferred to Hospital due to her condition worsening again.  Found a large blood clot in her right lung.  At this point she could no longer move herself due to weakness and continued neurological issues of her left side.  Heart continued to be strong.  She passed away on April 16, 2021.  Cause of death is unknown.

I got my 1st Pfizer vaccine on 1/22/21 and my second on 2/12/21.  Beginning in April of 2021, I started experiencing recurring sinus infections one after another.  I was treated for the first one in May with antibiotics.  I got another one the beginning of June, and was treated with antibiotics, and since that time, I have not been off antibiotics for more than 2-3 weeks without a sinus infection returning and necessitating the use of antibiotics, and at times, prednisone.  I had also been taking Zyrtec and Flonase daily to try to combat any allergies that might be causing these repeat infections.  It wasn't enough.  I had allergy testing done, and I reacted to almost everything on the test, and now I am on allergy shots.  I took allergy shots from the age of 10 to the age of 18.  I am now 36, and up until 2 months after my COVID vaccines, I had not had any significant allergy or sinus problems since I was a teenager.  It seems to me that this could be some type of immune system response to the vaccine, and my allergist has said this is possible since I went so many years without having major allergy issues and now am having such problems.  I have spent a lot of money on all of the office visits for all of these sinus infections, the antibiotics, and now the allergy shots.

He said we knew this was going to happen that's why I came with her.  He said she always passes out.  Said she did every time she received a flu shot and therefore she was expecting it. On May 7th, 10 hours after receiving my second Pfizer dose, at 12:40am, I started to experience bouts of muscle weakness and limb paralysis. By around 2:00am on Saturday, May 8th, I was fully paralyzed and unable to move or speak for at least 5 minutes. After regaining some movement and speaking ability, I yelled my wife?s name who immediately called 911 where I was transported to ED.  While in the ED on Saturday, May 8th, I received a full blood panel, urine analysis, CT with contrast, EKG, and neurology consultation to rule out possible TIA and CVA. All tests came back within normal limits and unremarkable.   During my CT scan, I began to experience a new episode of paralysis, lasting more than 20 minutes, that resulted in dyspnea. I am not claustrophobic and have never experienced dyspnea. After the scan, I was administered supplemental oxygen through a nasal cannula. My O2 SAT was in the high 90s for the majority of the morning. From 4:00 to 5:00am on Saturday, May 8th, my O2 SAT dropped to the low 80 range several times, but was able to regain normal O2 SAT. Around 6:00am, I recovered with no paralysis episodes and was monitored until 11:30am when I was discharged from the ED.  I was brought home and was functioning normally with no paralysis episodes for ~28 hours, until Sunday, May 9th at 9:30am, where I had another episode of full body paralysis with no dyspnea, in which paramedics took me back to the ED. At this visit, I had an MRI, which came back normal, and an EEG with a different neurologist. The results of the EEG were normal, even during these paralytic episodes, in which I had 3 during the EEG test.  I was admitted to the hospital Monday, May 10th for further observation and evaluation for at least the next two nights. My medical team consisted of a psychiatrist, neurologist, and generalist. I received his final diagnostic test of a lumbar puncture Tuesday, May 11th in the afternoon, which also came back unremarkable and within normal limits.  It is to note that these episodes of partial and full body paralysis come and go, sometimes at intervals of 30 seconds to as long as 25 minutes. During the episodes, I am unresponsive, but am able to breathe as well as cognitively alert with unimpaired memory. I can recall everything that has happened to me and I regain full function, motor and speech abilities once the episode passes.  After discharge on May 11th, I had no episodes until Wednesday June 11th late morning where I had another episode during a work video meeting. My wife called 911 and I was admitted to the hospital and observed until June 22nd. It is during this admission that another neurologist evaluated my episodes and diagnosed me with Functional Neurological Disorder.   Since June 22nd, I have had spouts of paralysis episodes here and there, latest episode being November 7th at 10:45pm. These episodes are inconsistent with unknown causes or triggers. It is to note that prior to getting the second Pfizer vaccine, my medical history was unremarkable as I am a healthy 29 year old who exercises regularly, eats well, and doesn?t smoke nor drink. There is no coincidence that the second COVID shot caused this serious adverse reaction of paralysis in which it is unknown that I will fully recover from.
LAB_DATA: All blood work, EEG, EKG, MRI, CT scan, and lumbar tap returned with normal/unremarkable results.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I've had mild heart palpitations since my late 20s that have never gone on for extended periods of time. I've managed them just fine with diet (figuring out my sensitivities, cutting out soda and other caffeine). After my 2nd vaccine, I had significant heart palpitations that delayed my getting to sleep. Over the next 3.5-4 months, I had occasional heart palpitations that kept  me up at night. They often came on if I were up late at night. I was no stranger to late nights BEFORE the vaccine and have had more late nights in the last month and a half and yet my palpitations are back to the low level from before.   I can't prove it's from the vaccine but I'd never had heart palpitations that bad in my life and I haven't had an event in the past couple of months.   In an appointment, I discussed the events with my naturopathic doctor who is also my primary care, Dr. (in answer to Item 21). I almost went to the ER one bad night but had a friend come over to watch me instead ( to see if he could get me to sleep and not go to an ER).
LAB_DATA: I haven't had tests yet. I plan to see a cardiologist to discuss next steps in the next couple of months.
OTHER_MEDS: Multi-vitamin (1/2 daily dose), vitamin b complex, vitamin D3, calcium, NAC
CUR_ILL: None (but this was my 2nd dose and I had a less impactful reaction to the first dose).
HISTORY: Minor heart palpitations, malabsorption as an infant with years of digestive issues and have had digestive issues even into adulthood. I work on my diet to manage it.
PRIOR_VAX: Minor, but had extreme fatigue and chills with the first covid 19 dose.
ALLERGIES: egg sensitivity (itchy), sesame (bad stomach aches), dairy sensitivity, anti biotic ointments such as neosporin and bacitracin

Patient did state he had his 2nd dose of Moderna, but it is not documented where this reporter can find the date (would have been sometime in April). He told this reporter he started to not feel well about 3 weeks after his 2nd dose. He eventually felt so bad he sought treatment in July. He was admitted 8/6/2021 with group B streptococcus agalactiae bacteremia, sepsis resulting in fever, encephalopathy and AKI (likely due to SBP).  TTE 8/17 showed severe AR and possible vegetation. TEE 8/18 confirmed infective endocarditis c/b AoV insufficiency. Patient is not an IV drug user.  Hospital course also complicated by Afib w RVR and was started on dilt drip, now off as patient's HR improved and he has had low BP in setting of likely worsening AoV insufficiency. Patient also with pulmonary edema periodically requiring 1-2L O2 . Furthermore, 8/22 patient had short run of torsades treated with Mag  Over the past several days, patient has developed hepatocardiorenal syndrome with worsening AKI. Transfer to ICU for consideration of CRRT initiation. Structural and CT surgery following due to severe AI. Tentative plan for TAVR. Patient with slowly worsening AMS as well, acute-subacutely worsening today. Thought to be due to hypoperfusion v acute illness. Cosyntropin stim test for hypothermia negative.  Patient arrived to ICU somnolent but arousable. HD catheter, PICC and A-line were placed for CRRT initiation, pressor initiation and hemodynamic monitoring respectively. Patient's hemodynamics continued to worsen evening after ICU transfer and temporary pacemaker was inserted and patient was paced with HR 90-110. Despite pressor support and temporary pacemaker, patient continued to worsen and was persistent in stating he no longer wished for current cares to continue. It was felt patient would not tolerate TAVR or liver transplant at this state as patient was not improving with pressor, CRRT, temporary pacemaker and hemodynamic support and as a result decision was made with family to transition patient to comfort cares. He ultimately succumbed into death on 8/26/2021
HISTORY: T2DM, ulcerative ileocolitis, primary sclerosing cholangitis, cirrhosis, and portal hypertension. Previously underwent liver transplant eval last year at ICVA with neg LHC and TTE. Wasn't sick enough to be listed

Several weeks after receiving my second dose of the Moderna vaccine, I began feeling pressure in the upper left side of my breast, as if a seatbelt was pushing on my chest. This sensation was present even when I had no clothing on.  It persisted for months.  I went to see my OB/GYN NP to see if I might have something going on in my breast. She conducted a breast exam and found nothing.  She gave me orders for a mammogram if it did not subside in a few more weeks, stating that sometimes the Covid vaccine affects lymph glands and causes inflammatory responses that can last a while.  I had a routine mammogram and breast ultrasound scheduled for September 22nd.  The sensation started decreasing, so I just waited until that September appointment.
