SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine just after 1700 on 10/26/2021. Due to my flu vaccine allergy I stayed for 30 minutes after to assess for reaction. My skin was crawling on my arm, but this is a normal reaction to vaccines for me since the flu allergy. They thought I looked flushed and I had random itching, but nothing on my face like they were concerned for. That evening my scalp was itchy so I took Benadryl. The following afternoon (10/27/21) when I woke up I felt like a truck had hit me, backed up, and ran me over again. All my joints hurt and my muscles were on fire/pins and needles when I moved. I had a severe headache that was centered between my eyes just above my hairline and at the base of my neck. I also started to develop a fever that did not lower with alternating APAP and Ibuprofen. The morning of the 28th my fever peaked at 102.2 and finally broke. The fire/pins and needles sensation finally began leaving my fingers so I could use my hands without feeling like I was going to drop things from the pain. The injection site was warm and red with blotchy skin surrounding it . The symptoms gradually improved but I had to see a doctor at urgent care on 11/2/21 because I had not been able to work since this had happened. I was still weak and tired easily. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalized (11/1/21);  COVID-19 positive (11/1/21); fully vaccinated  Discharge Provider: MD Primary Care Provider: DO Admission Date: 11/2/2021 Discharge Date: 11/4/2021 PRESENTING PROBLEM: Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus [U07.1, J12.82] HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 69 y.o. male  with pmhx of OSA on cpap, CAD s/p CABG and recent PCI in May on asa and plavix, HFpEF on torsemide, T2DM not on insulin, hx amyloidosis, HTN. He presented to the hospital for chief complaint of worsening SOB and chest discomfort. He was admitted for Elevated troponins and chest discomfort in the setting of dehydration and a COVID positive test.  Came from ER with chest discomfort and shortness of breath.  Patient was recently found to be COVID positive.  He is fully vaccinated but has not received a booster yet.  Chest angiogram thorax did reveal a right middle lobe pneumonia and was negative for PE.  Case was discussed with Cardiology given elevated troponin. They recommended heparin drip and transfer to another facility.  There was discussion about possible AFib, patient was given multiple IV Cardizem doses at facility before transfer to other facility.  At other facility, cardiology was consulted and thought this was only demand ischemia with his unchanged unremarkable EKGs and TEE. Troponins were elevated on admission but plateaud and in the context of the overall picture, were not concerning in their opinion.  Patient was admitted for elevated oxygen requirements and had a few episodes of hypoxia dropping into 87%, usually overnight. However this was determined to be 2/2 to not being on a CPAP machine and during periods of exertion. His saturations improved considerably afterwards and he continued to saturate in the mid to low 90s on room air. After two days of improved oxygen saturations, it was determined the patient would be best served by the COVID at home program. We discussed the patients care and plans moving forward to which they agreed. All questions were answered to the best of our ability with the given data. The patient was discharged in stable condition
LAB_DATA: CONSULTS / RECOMMENDATION: -Cardiology: EKG was nonischemic, troponin assay elevated but flat. Chest pain atypical and nonexertional. TEE with preserved EF and no valvular dysfunction. Considered to be nonischemic myocardial injury 2/2 COVID 19

Hospitalized (11.1.21);  COVID-19 vaccine (11.1.21);  fully vaccinated  Discharge Provider: Doctor Primary Care Provider at Discharge: Physician Assistant Admission Date: 11/1/2021 Discharge Date: 11/3/2021 PRESENTING PROBLEM: COVID-19  HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 55 y.o. female with a history of inflammatory arthritis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, who is not oxygen dependent, presents today with increasing shortness of breath and cough. She had received 2 doses of Pfizer vaccine for COVID-19.  Patient reported onset of fever, fatigue productive cough and shortness of breath 3 days ago. She noted coughing up green sputum.  She denied any chest pain, abdominal pain, nausea or vomiting, diarrhea or urinary symptoms.  She used her home inhalers without any improvement.  She tried to get into her PCP office but they had no openings so she scheduled a tele medicine visit today.  She noted the provider instructed her to be seen in the emergency department due to her coarse lung sounds and wheezing.  She proceeded to Emergency Department for evaluation.   Patient was hypoxic at 85% on room air and placed on 1 L of oxygen to maintain sats above 90%.  Laboratory studies unremarkable. EKG showed normal sinus rhythm with nonspecific ST and T wave abnormality. No change from previous EKG. COVID-19 positive.  Chest xray demonstrated hyperinflated lungs without acute cardiopulmonary process.  She was given IV Decadron and albuterol treatments but continued to require 1 L of oxygen.  Given her continued hypoxia she was transferred via EMS to Big Rapids Hospital for further care and treatment of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease exacerbation secondary to COVID-19 Pneumonia.  Patient was weaned to room air on 11/2 though her work of breathing warranted further monitoring. On 11/3 she had some dyspnea with exertion but was feeling well at rest; she felt confident to go home.  She will be discharged in stable condition on room air with a medrol dose pack and guaifenesin.  She understands she is recommended to follow up with her PCP to ensure resolution of Covid-19 with concomitant COPD exacerbation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client stated, "I am starting to itch on my arms and neck. I expected this to happen because I reacted the same way to my first and second dose of Pfizer." Co Lead RN observed red scratch marks on client's neck, upper chest, and inner forearms bilaterally near elbows. Client denied symptoms of shortness of breath or difficulty swallowing. Co Lead RN recommended to client the administration of Benadryl 50 mg PO once to alleviate mild allergic reaction symptoms. Client was in agreement, Secondary RN prepared and administered Benadryl 50 mg PO once to client at 12:24 PM. At 12:26 PM first set of vitals: B/P RA 132/76, pulse 103, O2 SAT 98%. Client stated, "my heart rate is usually high. It runs between 99-103 so that is normal for me. I am seeing a cardiologist for that to be cleared for my my gallbladder surgery." Client denied drinking caffeine and denied being a smoker. Client was provided 2 water bottles and 1 gram cracker. At 12:29 PM Co Lead RN recommended for client to call father on cell phone. Co Lead RN educated client to enroll in V-SAFE and follow up with PCP within 24 hours. Co lead RN educated client on when to call 911 or go to urgent care if adverse symptoms reappeared when client got home. At 12:55 client stated, "the itching is coming and going in waves, but I am starting to feel better. I know I've taken 100-125 mg of Benadryl to my reactions in the past." Client began to have slight rash appear above left eye brow. Co lead RN educated client that Benadryl 50 mg oral medication needed 30-45 minutes to begin having affect and could only be administered once per policy. Client appeared stable and stated, "I am starting to feel better with the itching." 1:00 PM vitals retaken by Secondary RN: B/P: 147/92, pulse 95, O2 SAT 100%. At 1:15 PM Co Lead RN reassessed client and she stated, "I am fine now. I am ready to go home." Co Lead RN confirmed that father was in the parking lot of vaccination site. Left eyebrow rash was no longer visible on client. No hives nor rash on upper extremities/neck/torso on client. At 1:17 PM Co Lead RN walked with client whom had a steady gait to parking lot and witnessed client meet up with father.
OTHER_MEDS: Medications: seroquel PO before bedtime for sleep, botox injections every 3 months for migraines, lamictal 100 mg PO daily.
HISTORY: Diagnosed with fibromyalgia, migraines, irritable bowel syndrome, gallbladder issues (pending surgery per client).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 11/07/2021 at 1523 client  date of birth 05/03/1999 (22-year old Male) was vaccinated in his Left Deltoid by RN for first-dose Johnson & Johnson (Lot#212A21A). At around 1529 as patient was seated following vaccination in the post-observation when staff MA called staff assistance/help. Charge RN and  2 post-observation RNs responded to the scene immediately around 1530 to find the patient lying on the ground. It was reported by post-observation RNs that patient had fell over from his chair and hit the Right anterior forehead.  RN reported that when she arrived on the scene she noticed the patients legs and right arm were shaking. Patient regained consciousness about 30 seconds after responding healthcare staff arrived to the scene. Patient was disoriented and RNs assessed that he had an area of redness to his Right anterior forehead. Patient stated he could not remember what happened just before he woke up on the floor. RNs assessed that patient was cold, clammy, and sweaty to touch. Patient was however able to verbalize to RNs his location, the date, the day of the week, and he remembered that he was at the vaccination site for his vaccine, A&Ox4. Patient denied any neck/back pain or discomfort. Patient sat up and denied any discomfort with movement, besides a headache. Patient was slowly assisted to wheelchair by RN staff, patient denied generalized discomfort but did exhibit generalized weakness upon ambulation. Initial HR at 1531 was 45 beats per minute (bpm), but improved by 1535 to HR 60 with a blood pressure (BP) of 115/51. Respirations and pulse oximetry remained within defined limits. By 1539 patient BP was 108/71 with HR 64 bpm.  Patient reported to RN staff that he had smoked marijuana at 1300 before coming in for his vaccination and had not eaten much food. Patient stated he felt better after drinking some apple juice. RN staff were about to call 911 but patient verbally declined that staff call for help. Patient was strongly encouraged by responding RN staff to go to the emergency room even though he declined. Patient stated ?I will be okay?. Patient declined further. Patient educated about risks of declining emergency assistance and informed by RN staff that if he had any changes in his current mental status such as exhibiting drowsiness, disorientation, or increased headache pain to call for emergency assistance immediately. Patient and patient?s wife verbalized understanding. Patient family informed to not let the patient go to sleep Patient stated he was feeling well. Patient wife was present during the event. Patient?s wife?s cousin who was also vaccinated would per the family be driving the patient home. Before leaving patient was moved in wheelchair by RN staff to lie down for 30 minutes on the secluded patient area on a medical cot. Patient was given a neuro assessment before leaving facility: patient bilateral hand grips strong, patient able to pull with both arms strongly, patient verbalized sensation to upper and lower extremities, patient extraocular movements within defined limits, patient face symmetrical, and patient states headache improved. Patient vital signs re-checked and stable. Patient dangled feet off medical cot and slowly stood, patient denied dizziness or weakness upon ambulation. Patient again refused emergency assistance but he and his wife stated they would call related to previous education given to them by RNs. Patient ambulated out of the clinic with wife without issue with a stable gait.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient reported that he smoked marijuana at 01:00 pm the day of vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 76 y.o female with h/o COPD on 2 L home oxygen, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, having been found unresponsive at HCF. With GCS 3 patient intubated, and mechanically ventilated at a local HCF. Diagnosed with COVID-19 and acinetobacter bacteremia. Right upper extremity with occlusive DVT in right brachial and basilic vein with nonocclusive thrombus in right axillary vein, initiated anticoagulation. Previous CT revealed no PE, However,  did show dilated pulmonary arteries. Repeat CT chest with contrast 09/14 revealed small amount of thrombus in left jugular and extensive chronic findings including goiter and marked enlargement of left pulmonary artery prior to previous.  Pt was transferred to another HCF for vascular surgery evaluation, advised nonsurgical, continuing anticoagulation. Pt persistently, off sedation, demonstrated no significant improvement with cognition/neurologic status. MRI brain 9/13 revealed no acute intracranial abnormally. EEG resulted abnormal with severe generalized slowing, consistent with severe encephalopathy, concern for possible epileptiform discharge prompted Neurology evaluation, provided Keppra. Pt was provided broad-spectrum antibiotics with cefepime and doxycycline, negative repeat blood cultures prompted discontinuation of antibiotics after 5 days of therapy. HCF provided counsel with family members regarding goals of care, ultimately, decision made to transition to comfort measure on the afternoon on 09/18/2021.  Pt succumbed to illness, suffered cardiopulmonary collapse as result of acute respiratory failure with hypoxemia secondary COVID-19 viral pneumonia at 1;45am on 09/29/2021

Pt was initially admitted to the medical COVID floor where he was initiated on Dexamethasone and Remdesivir therapies. His hypoxemia continued to worsen and he required initiation of noninvasive positive pressure ventilation and was eventually transferred to the ICU on 10/28/2021 for ongoing care and management in the setting of refractory hypoxemia. His ICU course was initially complicated by delirium. His condition continued to worsen and was intubated on 10/30/2021 in the setting of impending respiratory/cardiac arrest. He began to experience increasing  hypotension as well and required initiation of vasopressors. Given the history of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, cardiologist was consulted and Pt was additionally placed on Dobutamine. He had worsening acidemia despite optimization of ventilator settings and required initiation on renal replacement therapy on 11/02/2021. Unfortunately, he continued to decompensate and on the evening of 11/04/2021, the patient did suffer of a cardiac arrest. Unfortunately Pt did succumb to his critical illness on the evening of 11/04/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: There were two adverse events.   #1 The next morning when I woke up (3/9/2021), I had two large blisters just below the nape of my neck.  When I touched them, they burst.  They were extremely painful and took several weeks to heal.  The area was painful or sensitive for several months.  #2 I don't know if this event was related or not, but VSafe called me and told me to file a VAERS report...  On March 20th, I experienced an incident where I had crackling in my throat (I could hear a sound like crumpling cellophane), I had trouble breathing.  I just couldn't catch my breath and couldn't take a deep breath.  My heart was racing.  I used an inhaler, but I didn't think it did anything at the time.  Just when things started going black, I told my husband to call an ambulance.  I sat down on the bed and the darkness receded.  I don't know if the inhaler worked or if my adrenaline kicked in...  but I felt a little better, but still had trouble breathing, so we went to the Emergency Room.
LAB_DATA: March 20th, 2021 - EKG, CTA Chest (angiogram), Chest X-Ray, CT Neck without contrast  Their tests were all geared towards checking if I had a heart attack.  I did not.  They prescribed prednisone and had me follow up with my cardiologist.
OTHER_MEDS: levothyroxine,  Irbesartan-HCTZ multivitamin, vitamin D3, calcium

Patient had an adverse event GBS (Guillen barre syndrome) and was hospitalized for 3 weeks. He did not believe it is close enough to be an allergy. Caller reported he couldn't talk, walk down the hallway, so he went to the hospital for a suspected stroke. However, after the hospital did an ultrasound and some other tests, the results were negative for a stroke or TIA and he was discharged. On that Wednesday (caller is unsure of date), 2 days after being discharged from the emergency room, the patient went back to same hospital. When he arrived, his son got a wheelchair because the patient couldn't move. The patient asked to see a neurologist, who immediately diagnosed him with variety of GBS and did a spinal tap to confirm. After the spinal tap results came back positive, the hospital gave him a special IVIP for 5 days in a row.  Company's comment: This case concerns a 71-year-old male patient with a history of allergies, who experienced the unexpected, serious (hospitalization, disability and medically significant) adverse events of special interest Guillain-Barre syndrome and Bell's palsy. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received Moderna booster on 11/5/21 at 11am. During the night, Patient tried to get out of bed to go to the bathroom and couldn't stand. She fell and laid on the floor with her head on the corner of a dresser drawer until 8am on 11/6 when her niece that she lives with found her. Patient had slight standing issues (tried a few times to stand due to muscular soreness and weakness in legs) since shortly after her first Moderna shot on 2/11/21 at Pharmacy. Her 2nd dose was on 3/11/21 same place. Standing became increasingly harder but she was able to stand on her own then walk fine with no assistance anytime. Less than 24 hours after her booster we found her on the floor, unable to stan unable to stand on her own and with much muscular pain in her legs and back. We called 911 & went to Hospital around 8am on 11/6/21. They did a CAT scan to rule out stroke & bloodwork. She was discharged with a walker around 2pm same day. Doctors suspected covid booster shot reactions and said they were seeing many patients with covid shot reactions.  Patient was unable to stand at all, even with 3 adults trying to get her up and she was still having muscular pain. She stared and did not act right. The top of her thigh and hip area were extremely swollen. We called 911 again around 10pm on 11/6/21 to return to same hospital because she was totally immobile, unable to stand and barely walk even with a walker. A hip xray, covid test, more bloodwork and ultrasound were done - all negative. Doctors suspect Moderna booster reaction. She will be receiving physical therapy, IV antibiotics (slightly elevated white count) and oral Ibuprofin for inflammation. On 11/7 she was doing better. Patient is still having a hard time standing but more alert and able to walk better with a walker. She is still hospitalized on 11/8.
LAB_DATA: 11/6 & 11/7/21: CAT scan of head, bloodwork, ultrasound on legs, hip xray
CUR_ILL: slight problem standing - able to stand & self care fully

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my second Moderna Covid-19 vaccine shot on March 28, 2021.  The shot was injected high up on my arm at the curve of my shoulder.  Approximately 3 hours later, while sitting on my couch watching television, I began to experience significant pain in my upper left arm, shoulder and, to a lesser degree, my forearm just below the elbow.  The pain was so severe, I could not lift my arm without assistance from my opposite hand.  The severe pain lasted about 3 days, then began to slightly subside.  The pain leveled out at approximately a 6-7 out of ten, about 4-5 days post injection.   After about 9-10 days, I made an appointment with my PCP and after a week or two of taking Ibuprofen with little to no improvement, I requested physical therapy.  I began my course of PT on April 19, 2021.  At my first visit, I explained my symptoms to my physical therapist and he asked me if I had ever heard of SIRVA.  It was his opinion that I had absolutely suffered an injury from the injection and diagnosed me with SIRVA.  I have now been treating for over 6 months and although I have had some improvement, I often regress for several days to weeks at a time when trying to add exercises that involve even the slightest amount of weight; i.e., 1-2 pounds.  In addition, one area of my upper arm continues to experience significant pain with certain movements and I can still experience levels of pain ranging from 4-7, depending on the movement.  I also saw a physiatrist on May 24, 2021 who, upon examination, advised me that I was presenting with symptoms of a rotator cuff injury.  My physical therapist and I have discussed the possible need for an MRI at this time.  On October 5, 2021, I had an MRI of my left shoulder which revealed:  1) Moderate anterosuperior rotator cuff tendinosis with high-grade undersurface tearing of the supraspinatus tendon extending into the anterior fibers of the infraspinatus tendon, as described.  2) Moderate acromioclavicular joint osteoarthritis and mild subacromial/subdeltoid bursitis. 3) Small subacromial spur. 4) Thickened edematous inferior joint capsule, and infiltration and edema within the rotator interval fate, findings that can be seen in adhesive capsulitis (frozen shoulder).  On October 28, 2021, I followed up with an orthopedic surgeon.  After physical examination and reviewing the results of the MRI, it was his opinion that my frozen shoulder was the main cause of the pain, reduced range of motion and reduced strength I am experiencing.  I received a cortisone shot in my shoulder and it was his hope that my symptoms would subside; however, he advised that he expected my recovery time to be between 18 months and 2 years.  At this time, I continue to have reduced range of motion, reduced strength and pain with certain movements of my left arm.  I also experience achiness and/or pain at rest on occasion.  I am still unable to extend my left arm straight up over my head, the elbow remains somewhat bent and my right arm extends approximately 3 inches above my left.  I cannot reach straight out to the side and lift my arm, with or without holding anything.  I am also unable to reach behind me to retrieve an item, nor am I able to reach behind my back to adjust clothing or scratch my back.  I am also restricted from laying on my stomach and being able to place my left arm straight, extending above my head (as in yoga's child pose), or extend it straight out to the side.  All of these motions cause pain, sometimes significant, and discomfort.  Although the doctor is hopeful for full recovery, due to my slow progress and many regressions, I am not totally convinced that this will be the case.  It is my understanding that at times, this type of injury does not fully resolve.  Only time will tell.  I am currently continuing with a home exercise program and following up with my physical therapist on a monthly basis.
LAB_DATA: X-Rays - No significant findings MRI - 10/5/21 (See response to no. 18)
OTHER_MEDS: Atorvastatin, Atenolol, Pantroprazole, baby aspirin, multi-vit

HPI: Patient is a 45 year old man with a recent COVID 19 illness (August) requiring ICU stay and immunosuppressive therapy was admitted on 11/4 for altered mental status. He felt almost fully recovered, was doing work around the house, cooking meals and improving however last week he had a week of feeling more sleepy, eating less and his wife said sleeping 16 hours at times. He developed acute nausea with diaphoresis and chills and word finding issues the morning of his admit. He presented with a WBC and CSF revealed a pleocytosis. Workup was unremarkable-both cultures and images and symptoms resolved quickly. He was discharged but had a seizure on the way home and returned for further therapy. Today he states that he has a bad headache but is otherwise feeling improved. His meningitis therapy was reinitiated on admit.  Impression: Patient is a 45 year old man with post covid syndrome including tachycardia, weakness and now with seizures likely as a sequelae of the disease. His initial presentation included an extensive workup with negative imaging, labs with a leukocytosis that resolved quickly and CSF studies that had a lympo/mono predominance, all consistent with seizure activity. Patient said that he had his flu shot Thursday and he wondered if it could have contributed by causing more inflammation. It is possible the shot caused an increase in his overall inflammatory state. Vaccines have been described as causing aseptic meningitis although these are rare events. We will be sure to report this occurrence to the VAERS database.    Assessment/Plan: 1. CSF pleocytosis, aseptic meningitis- likely seizure related. Ok to d/c antivirals, antimicrobials. Vaccine induced vs part of the sequelae of long covid. Difficult to discern. Will report to VAERS 2. Seizure d/o- per neurology 3. Leukocytosis- resolved 4. Post covid, long covid diagnosis- continue to follow with appropriate consultants. I recommended vaccination for covid once symptoms have resolved and closer to 6-8 months following his initial infection.

I received the vaccine on Tuesday, mid-morning, on October 26, 2021. It felt like I was having an inflammatory response by the afternoon. The soreness at the injection site increasingly grew in intensity and the joints throughout my body were radiating pain. I felt awful. I contracted Covid in June of 2021, but this felt worse than the actual symptoms. I self-medicated with 600 mg of Ibuprofen and would alternate with Tylenol. These feelings persisted and by Saturday, October 30, 2021, I started having an upset stomach. I didn't make the connection, and ate lightly the rest of the day. The next day, Sunday, it felt like my entire abdomen was on fire. I tried every home remedy I could think of. Taking Tums, Mylanta, Miralax, and  I went on a liquid diet, but nothing helped. I could not sleep Sunday or Monday night because the pain was so intense. Early Tuesday morning, around 4am, I drove to our local Emergency Room. They gave me IV, administered anti-inflammatory medication, calcium, and performed a CAT scan. The CAT scan revealed the thickening of my colon lining, but no blockages or life threatening issues, so I was discharged. with a prescription for Pepcid. I went to my PCP the next day, and she prescribed Prilosec. When that didn't provide relief, I went back to the hospital on Wednesday and was admitted until Friday, and discharged with gastritis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt with progressively worsening cervical neck pain, starting  2-3 days after his 2nd dose of the Pfizer COVID19 mRNA vaccine. Pt initially went to multiple chiropractors before finally seeing family medicine physician in October.   Xray cervical spine showed concern for discitis/osteomyelitis. Urgent MRI ordered, which showed severe discitis/osteomyelitis with an epidural phlegmon. Per Radiology, Pt very lucky that he had a wide spinal canal; otherwise, he would have had severe compression of his spine at C4-T1 (C3-5 innervate the diaphragm; "C3/4/4 keep the man alive").   Pt was sent urgently to the hospital and was admitted; however, neurosurgery and ID at admitting hospital did not feel comfortable performing a biopsy or treating empirically without a biopsy. Pt was transported to the Clinic 4 days later, where emergency neurosurgery was performed to stabilize the spine and to obtain bony cultures; Pt had complete erosion of C6 and C7 vertebrae (both anteriorly and posteriorly) at that time. Pt was discharged on PO Cipro; culture was unremarkable.
LAB_DATA: Xray, cervical spine 10/20/21:  "1. Abnormality centered at the C6-C7 levels with height loss of C6 and C7 as well as ill-defined inferior endplate of C6 and superior endplate of C7. Findings may be infectious/inflammatory in etiology in the absence of known trauma. Discitis-osteomyelitis must be considered. 2. Retrolisthesis of C6 on C7 as well as anterolisthesis of C4 on C5, C5 on C6, and C7 on T1. 3. Widening of the interspinous distance at C6-C7."  MRI C-spine 10/21/21: "Severe discitis and osteomyelitis at C6-C7 with a probable small ventral epidural phlegmon causing effacement of anterior thecal sac without compression of the spinal cord... The epidural phlegmon extends into the right and left C6-C7 neural foramina. Some kyphosis resulting from the bony destruction with associated straining of the C6-C7 interspinous ligament is demonstrated."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 2/22/2021 at about 1:00PM, I received my second dose of Pfizer. Within about an hour, I felt a little woozy and nauseous. I ended up feeling nauseous for most of the day and had an annoying discomfort in my stomach. I was still able to eat, but I couldn't eat as much as usual. I had a previous history of gallstones, which had caused me no trouble prior to this time, and I now suspect that the vaccine may have aggravated the situation. I continued to have nausea and stomach discomfort off and on from 2/22/2021 up until the day in late March 2021 when the nausea and stomach discomfort had become so bad that I went to the ER at Medical Center. (I don't remember the exact date.) While at the ER, I underwent various tests that included a CAT scan and a stomach X-ray or ultrasound. I had taken omeprazole for the discomfort and nausea, but it hadn't helped. The ER staff advised me to see a doctor, so I made an appointment to see a gastroenterologist. Dr. advised me to get an endoscopy and a test for my gallbladder function whose name I don't remember. I underwent the endoscopy at Dr. practice and the gallbladder test at Medical Center. I was informed that my gallbladder was functioning at 1% and that I should see a surgeon. I contacted Dr., who removed my gallbladder via laparoscopy on 5/25/2021 at Hospital. Dr. told me that the gallbladder was inflamed and had many small black stones. Also, despite being fully vaccinated, I had a breakthrough case of COVID19, which I tested positive for on 10/2/2021.
OTHER_MEDS: Atenolol Amlodipine Hydrochlorothiazide Fenofibrate Vitamin D (prescription, taken once a week) Centrum Silver CoQ10 (200 mg) Zinc (50 mg) Vitamin C (500 mg) Magnesium (500 mg) Eliquis (5 mg, taken twice daily) Occasionally Tylenol

I have never had anything  this before and have not recently changed my soap, detergent, or moisturizer cream.   I get stitches from biopsy out tomorrow.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 7 hours post-admninistration, I awoke in the middle of the night with debilitating shoulder pain. I was unable to move my shoulder and had little to no range of motion. While I knew that I would experience injection site pain (considering I've received countless vaccinations including the first two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine), this was different as this was in my shoulder bursa, and I was unable to move my arm. I tried taking painkillers and using ice, to no avail. I tried doing small range of motion exercises by lifting my left arm up using my right hand, to no avail as it only made the pain sharper and worse. For the next 6 days I continue to have debilitating shoulder pain, and am making an appointment with my orthopedist. As someone who has given vaccines throughout the pandemic, I know that this was not a problem with the vaccine, but with the injector's lack of skill and/or carelessness. She did not use the correct method to landmark the injection site (such as the Z-track method), and over-confidently injected way too high up on my arm and straight into the bursa resulting in SIRVA (or a SIRVA-like reaction). I still do not have even close to full function in the arm. Any muscular soreness has gone away but the joint pain/bursa pain has not.
LAB_DATA: I have not yet gone for testing as I wanted to be sure it wasn't just debilitating reaction pain. Now that the classic post-vaccine symptoms have resolved, I now know it had nothing to do with the vaccine or its chemical makeup in the slightest. It was all in the injector's poor technique/carelessness.
OTHER_MEDS: Levetiracetam ER (1500 mg PO BID), Lamotrigine ER (50 mg PO BID), Folic Acid (2 mg PO BID), Vitamin D, Vitamin C, Tri-Lo Estarylla tricyclic OCP

17 year old male with no significant past medical history who presents with chest pain and elevated troponins following his second Covid vaccination. He received the dose 11/3/21.  After his vaccine, he had flu-like symptoms, similar to after his first dose. On 11/6, he felt mild SOB in the afternoon without associated pain.  Later that night at 0100 the morning of admission, he experienced left sided, non-radiating, sharp pleuritic chest pain.  Taking deep breaths made the pain worse and there was nothing he could do to make the pain better. He experienced no nausea, vomiting, numbness, tingling, jaw claudication, or diaphoresis. He does admit to tender lymph nodes in his left axilla, which he also had after his first dose of the vaccine.   He presented to an outside emergency room this morning. At that time he was found to have tachycardia, with an EKG notable only for sinus tachycardia. Troponin was elevated at that time. Due to concerns for myocarditis, he was transferred to our facility for echo evaluation, which showed good function. His pain also improved. As such, he was admitted for ongoing monitoring.

A few weeks after the second shot, I developed an intermittent left bundle branch block (LBBB). Initially this block was occurring with elevated heart rate, but at very low (usually below 100bmp, sometimes as low as 70bpm) . I have an Apple Watch ECG which is able to record the arrythmia when I feel it, and reviewing my previously recorded ECG's I had no indication of an LBBB this prior to this time. I subsequently had a full workup including Echocardiogram, Stress Echo, 24hr monitor, blood tests (lyme, covid, calcium etc) as well as a Cardiac MRI. None of those tests have determined any functional issue with my heart, nor any obvious scarring or inflammation. It's not fully clear if this was related to my vaccine other than time of onsite was highly correlated with my second shot. Since the initial issues in May, I have trended towards better, with the LBBB usually now only occurring at very high heart rates ranging from 160-180bpm. It however has not gone away completely and this interferes with my ability to exercise (hike, mountain bike) because I must restrict my exertion to keep below the trigger (which is variable and hard to predict).
LAB_DATA: Echocardiogram Stress Echo Blood work Cardiac MRI

Death Summary   Date of Admission: 10/17/2021   Date of Death:10/30/2021   Reason for Hospital Admission (Admitting Diagnosis): Acute Hypoxemic Respiratory Failure   Hospital Course and Significant Findings: Patient was a 72 Y male with history of renal transplant in 2017, on chronic immunosuppression (cellcept, prograf, pred), CKD who presented with 2 weeks of productive cough, decreased appetite and a positive COVID test on 10/11. Despite being vaccinated on 04/2021 with J&J. In the ED, the patient desatted (87%) with ambulation. He was admitted for hypoxemic respiratory failure. He became gradually more confused, developed worsening kidney injury. The patient also had a CT with evidence of an intramuscular hematoma attributed to coughing with supratherapeutic INR. This was reversed with Kcentra. For his COVID pneumonia treatment, he was given regneron, decadron 6mg, remdesivir for 5 days and tocilizumab once on 10/24. He had multiple rapid responses called on 10/24 and 10/26 for increasing O2 requirements. His confusion and respiratory status worsened and on 10/27 he was admitted to the ICU. He was intubated on 10/29, found to have elevated troponin, worsening renal failure and CT findings of cavitary lesions and severely damaged lungs. This was relayed to the patient's family and he was ultimately transitioned to comfort care. The patient died at 2:40am, on 10/30/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 20 year old, referred for consideration by primary team for exemption to the COVID-19 vaccination.  The patient reports he was OK around 5-6 October.  On 6 October he received the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine in the morning and then found that he injured/twisted his right ankle.  He injured it one more time that same day and then it had persistent numbness over the top of the foot and difficulty raising the foot.  About a week later he noticed, in addition to those persistent symptoms in the right foot, that his hands/fingers were tingling and he had some trouble with fine motor use.  He then received multiple other vaccinations recorded on 12 October are vaccinations for adenovirus, twinrix, polio, menveo, menactra, Tdap, varicella.  MEDPROS not available for confirmation (menactra and menveo would not normally be given together as they are both meningitis vaccines).  His symptoms persisted and he sought care from primary care, was referred for specialty care with physical medicine and neurology which ultimately led him referred for consideration of IVIG treatment for presumptive diagnosis of AIDP.  Here the neurology service feels the diagnosis may be AIDP or HNPP, but neither diagnosis is conclusive.  Past medical history is significant for receipt of most childhood vaccines with the exception of HAV and potentially one MMR.  He had HBVx3, Dtap x4, IPV x3, HiB x4, PCV x4, varicella x1 and MMR x1.  Mom reports that the patient had some developmental/speech delays and required an IEP and he had low muscle tone requiring physical therapy until the 2nd or 3rd grade.  She also noted he would get large swelling at the sites of the vaccines which concerned her (she has a medical background so could compare to others) and he would have several hours of an inconsolable cry after Dtap vaccination.  Other than that no surgeries, allergies, medications.  No recent illness prior to the onset of the symptoms in the foot.  No diarrhea, no fever before or after symptoms.  No rash including hives, angioedema, eczema at any time.
LAB_DATA: The neurology service performed EMG studies which were abnormal and performed a spinal tap.
PRIOR_VAX: The patient reports large local reactions and prolonged crying with Dtap as a child

Healthy pregnancy with no complications. Received COVID booster shot at 33 weeks pregnant. No side effects or symptoms for myself (mom) after booster. Baby was born about 4.5 weeks later at 37 weeks, 6 days. Normal uncomplicated labor and delivery, but baby was found immediately to have a prematurely closed ductus arteriosus with subsequent pulmonary hypertension and right ventricular hypertrophy. Cardiologists taking care of her suspect that the PDA closed a few weeks before birth, possibly corresponding with the timing of the COVID booster. To date, there has been no known other cause of the PDA closure (no maternal medication contraindications, etc). Baby's due date was 11/17/21, born on 11/2/21. Birth weight was 8lbs 6oz. Baby is still hospitalized in the ICU, ventilated and struggling cardiovascularly.

On July 17th, around 6PM, I felt a sudden, abrupt stiffness in the bottom of my neck to the top of my neck.  My neck became incredibly tense.  I started vomiting.   Throughout the night I felt a lot of head pressure that I'd never felt before.   When I woke up around 9AM, on July 18th, I had an extremely excruciating headache.  At that point, we decided to go the ER at the Hospital.  We got to the hospital around Noon.   They did the initial CT scan and found a brain bleed.  Around 3PM, they transferred me, via ambulance, to another hospital, which has better capacity to perform neurological procedures. I was at that Hospital from July 18th to 28th in the ICU.  Diagnosis was Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
LAB_DATA: Around 6PM, July 18th I had a diagnostic cerebral angiogram which showed Subarachnoid hemorrhage with hydrocephalus.  On July 19th I had a MRI of the brain and cervical spine.  I had another cerebral angiogram on July 26 which showed vasospasm.
OTHER_MEDS: I was not taking any medications or supplements during the time of the vaccine.

I went in to see Dr. who put me on a medicine to help me sleep, I saw a spinal surgeon the next week and went over MRI, both Dr. and the spine specialist said this was due to the vaccine, not my spine. But on Oct 3 2021 I was urinating blood and went to the ER. The ER put me on 3L of oxygen because they saw my oxygen level drop on the pulse-ox.  I was admitted from Oct 4 2021 to Oct 8 2021.  I had a stress test,  echocardigram,  CT SCAN,  lab work,  chest x-ray and all test seemed to come back ok. I was walked by the nurse with a pulse-ox on and within 30 feet my oxygen level dropped from 97 to 82 so a lung Dr was called in.  She ordered a pulmonary function test,  blood gas test and a echocardigram bubble study.   I was discharged on Oct 8 2021 with oxygen to have at home.  I was sent to a facility for a possible pulmonary avm. SYMPTOM_TEXT: client was verbalizing anxiousness prior to vaccination and stated that client stated "feeling dizzy" while walking to the observation room post vaccination. Co Lead rn observed client to be visibly shaking and gripping boyfriend's hand with both of her hands. Client was A&Ox2 to person and situation. Co Lead RN determined client could not ambulate towards observation room and went to retrieve wheelchair. Client was safely transferred into wheelchair with two nurse assist and then taken to observation room. Secondary RN set up gravity chair in observation room for client. Client then transferred into gravity chair from wheelchair with two nurse assist. Co Lead RN recommended for client to lower her face mask and take long deep breaths. At 11:15 AM first vitals taken on client: BP LA 170/100, pulse 78, O2 SAT 98%. Client stated, "I am diagnosed with anxiety by a doctor and take anxiety medications for it. Last time I was this anxious around needles was about 3 months ago. I always begin to feel short of breath." Client was unable to remember her medication name. Client stated, "I forgot to take my anxiety medication today, I have the medication bottle in my car." Client was provided water to drink but declined snacks. Co Lead RN observed client to become more relaxed and was answering questions with smiling and giggling throughout conversation. Client stated, "I am starting to feel better" and was now observed to be A&Ox4. Co Lead RN educated client to follow up with primary care physician. Boyfriend confirmed that he would be driving both of them home. Co Lead RN stated to client to continue taking deep breaths and relax for another 15 minutes. At 11:36 second set of vitals: BP LA 132/88, Pulse 68, O2 SAT 98%. Secondary RN educated client on the importance of taking anxiety medication before any procedure she knows that would trigger an episode and to have them on her person. Client verbalized understanding and then stated, "I am ready to go home now." Co Lead RN walked as standby assist with client as she walked with a steady gait (boyfriend at her side) outside the facility at 11:42 AM.
PRIOR_VAX: Anxiety

He asked the mom if she had food or drink recently. She said the pt had a snack and water during the car ride to Pharmacy. The pharmacist offered to call Emergency, but the mom said she would be fine in a minute. Another employee got help from the front end manager who paged for further management assistance. The pharmacist gave the patient a bottle of water.  Two AGMs and the pharmacy manager then responded to the page. The patient was seated and drinking water upon arrival. The pharmacy manager told an AGM to call Emergency and the other AGM got a churro for the pt to eat. The pharmacy mgr asked the mom if we could move the patient to a laying down position on a bench nearby in which the AGM helped. The pt laid flat with her head in her mom's lap. The mom refused the EMS service to go to the hospital. The patient finished her churro and left with her mom.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I wanted to report an incident that happened today at a pharmacy when my daughter was receiving the COVID vaccine.   I brought my 7 year old to the local pharmacy today at 1 pm. The nurse who administered the vaccine wasn't wearing a mask or gloves. She put on one glove when she actually injected my daughter, but wasn't wearing any when handling the vial or the syringe.   When she found out my daughter's age, she unnecessarily commented, "oh she's so young." After my daughter received the vaccine, and we were waiting, I overheard the pharmacist and nurse disagreeing about the amount of vaccine that had been given to my daughter, and the other children that day. The pharmacist felt the nurse hadn't given enough in the syringe, neither was going to tell me, but luckily I overheard them and confronted them.  The pharmacist felt the nurse had used too much saline (1.85 ml) to dilute the vaccine, and as a result the nurse should have given a larger amount. The nurse disagreed, and they told me they were waiting for a "higher up" at the pharmacy to weigh in.  The nurse said many times that I should not worry about the amount, and just to watch my daughter for side effects.  I now feel that she purposely administered a lower dose. I'm not sure if my daughter received a correct dose, and am quite frustrated that this has happened.   I want to report this so that someone can help me determine if she received a correct dose, and what our next steps should be. And also, to have someone look into the nurse and the incident, so that this doesn't happen to any other children and families.   I have reported this to the pharmacy, and am awaiting a response from the District Manager. I'm not sure if you can help, or if this is relevant to you, but someone provided your contact info and suggested I share as you are researching a similar incident at another pharmacy.   I'm happy to answer any questions you might have. Thank you!

Was exposed to COVID on 10/28/2021. When it started, I thought I was really carsick. I was a little bit dizzy and nauseated. About 04:30 on Sunday, it came on really sudden. I couldn't hand out Halloween candy. The nausea lasted for about 6 days. I had a really bad headache. I took Tylenol for the headache helped enough to fall asleep. Woke up and headache was a little better but was still nauseated. I was dizzy. On the second day, I had chills - cold to the bone. Headache would come and go. The initial night was the worst time for the headache. The next day, the fatigue started. I had significant reactions to the COVID vaccines, and this fatigue was just like that. It came on pretty sudden. My eyelids felt so heavy. I couldn't keep them open. It wasn't because I was tired at the time just heavy. I had a little bit of muscle ache, but it wasn't really bad. The fatigue lasted until this past Saturday from day 3 to day 7. I feel fine today. I normally run a very low temperature, but I was running a 98.7 for me that was a temperature. I had the temperature day 2, 3, and 4 and then I noticed it anymore. No treatment used Tylenol. I had a little bit of a runny nose, but I normally take 2 allergy meds a day, so I didn't take anything else for. The nausea and the fatigue were the most pronounced things for me. Had flu vaccine two weeks after I had the 3rd booster, I think I had it on the 10th of October. It was at another Pharmacy

Shortly after getting vaccinated, patient sat down for a 15 min wait period. She immediately started having trouble breathing and complained of stomach pain and a desire to vomit. I took her to the bathroom, she started getting hot, complained that it was getting harder to breathe, and seemed a little confused/didn't register what I was saying to keep her calm and wanting her to get out of the bathroom so we could speak with the pharmacist for help. I got her out, and the pharmacist helped me to refill her albuterol prescription (she needs it so rarely, when she has a cold, we didn't have it with us + she's never had an adverse reaction to a vaccine). That helped immediately. She drank some water. She then went back to the bathroom and had diarrhea. After that, we hung out for another 30+ minutes. Her breathing stabilized, she didn't need more albuterol, and she said she felt much better.  We're still less than 12 hrs. out from the vaccine as I write, so we are monitoring for any symptoms, and encouraging her to rest and drink fluids. I've also contacted her dr. to give a heads up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was given Janssen Covid 19 Vaccine on 11/8/2021. Patient waited 15 minutes in the pharmacy before being rung out at the register for his vaccination. After signing for his prescription (after waiting 15 minutes in the pharmacy), patient stated that he felt dizzy and was going to sit for a little while longer. When walking back to the pharmacy waiting area, the patient had a fainting spell and collapsed on the floor. When responding to the patient, he was awake and alert. Patient states that he did not hit his head when falling. Patient was able to sit up and was given water and a cold/wet paper towel per his request. After a few minutes, the patient was able to get up and stated he felt better. Pharmacist had patient take blood pressure, which was recorded at 110/76. Patient declined further medical care. The patient was here alone and stated that there was no one in the area to call for a ride. Pharmacy staff offered to call friend/relative for assistance or to call 911 for patient - the patient declined. The patient stated that he felt well enough to drive home and was instructed to call the pharmacy upon arrival home. Patient called around 7 PM on 11/8/21 stating that he was doing okay and that he had made it home safely. Pharmacist will follow up with patient tomorrow (11/9/21).
LAB_DATA: Blood Pressure approximately 10 minutes after incident = 110/76 mmHg

Hospitalized (10.28.21 - still admitted); COVID-19 positive (10.28.21);  fully vaccinated PLUS booster CHIEF COMPLAINT:  Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: Patient is a 70 y.o. female who presents today with past medical history of obesity, AF on eliquis, OSA, HTN, venous stasis who presents with shortness of breath. She had developed a cough that started approximately 6 days ago after receiving her booster Pfizer COVID vaccine. She developed diarrhea 2 days later. She has not had any fevers or chils. She lives with her husband and states that she started feeling more short of breath today. She began having difficulty with ambulating around her home to just use the restroom. She has no history of CHF, COPD but does have a history of atrial fibrillation.  In the ED, she received 1 dose of Rocephin for presumed UTI. She also received 125 mg Solumedrol and 500 ml of normal saline. EKG showed atrial fibrillation with RVR at 112 beats per minute. She also received Lasix 20 mg IV. Acute hypoxic respiratory failure Sepsis COVID-19 pneumonia Obesity, BMI 52 Patient presented with tachycardia, leukocytosis tachypnea, hypoxia.  Upon arrival, she was placed on high-flow nasal cannula 50 L. Patient is significant respiratory distress, she is short of breath with short sentences.  Notably, she is fully vaccinated and received her booster shot 6 days ago. Tested Positive: 10/28 Day of Illness #6 Oxygen Requirements: HFNC 50 L, 65% FiO2 - Decadron: s/p Solumedrol x 1,  - Remdesivir: start loading dose - Daily CBC, CMP, D-dimer. - DVT Prophylaxis: Eliquis - Oxygen PRN - Immodium for diarrhea - monitor I/o with goal of net negative              - consider Foley Daily renal and liver function monitoring for kidney and liver toxicity due to Remdesvir is required. Progress Note from 11/8/21:  Plan of the day:  -Continue lung protective ventilation, we will attempt decreasing the PEEP to 12 -Repeat CXR if she develop any decompensation to assess for development of PTX -Keep paralyzed for now given worsening hypoxia and pneumomediastinum  This patient is critically ill and is requiring active support and intensive surveillance to prevent life threatening clinical deterioration. -Worsening hypoxia overnight, CT chest showed pneumomediastinum and small apical PTX. ETT was pulled up,  -CXR this morning with satisfactory position of ETT tube, I could not visualize PTX on left side.  dexamethasone changed to solumedrol and Started on Zosyn and vancomycin overnight,
LAB_DATA: Assessment and Plan Acute respiratory failure with hypoxia Assessment & Plan Due to COVID-19 pneumonia. CXR 10/29 with diffuse bilateral infiltrates but there is a more distinct lobar pattern in the RUL. Cannot rule out a secondary bacterial pneumonia. She was not able to maintain her O2 sats on HFNC and a nonrebreather and was placed on BIPAP. This is not an ideal situation because she is not expected to improve quickly and cannot tolerate any oral intake/nutrition while on continuous BIPAP. However, she is currently maintaining acceptable O2 sats on BIPAP and work of breathing also appears to be acceptable. Her body habitus places her at higher risk for difficult intubation as does her oxygen requirements. It is reasonable to keep her on BIPAP overnight as long as her work of breathing is stable and oxygenation can be maintained but she will likely need intubation in the morning unless FiO2 requirements have improved to the point she can transition back to HFNC + nonrebreather.  - continue ceftriaxone empirically for possible bacterial pneumonia - Ok to continue BIPAP 12/6, FiO2 95% for now. Low threshold to intubate if work of breathing or oxygen requirements worsen any further.  - Agree with continued diuresis for goal net fluid balance negative - Steroids and remdesivir as noted under COVID-19 pneumonia.

Patient states that he woke up at 5am with shortness of breath. He checked his oxygenation and was oxygenating at 85%. He states that he had chest pain located at the center of his chest. He states the pain did not radiating to his arms or jaw. He increased his oxygen to 8L and his shortness of breath and chest pain improved. His chest pain resolved with improved oxygenation. He endorses associated chills, but denied any fever or worsening cough. He received two COVID vaccines. He presented to the hospital at the instruction of his home nurse.  Patient endorsed right lower extremity pain. He has chronic wounds and recently underwent stenting In the ED, patient was tachycardic. He originally was oxygenating well on home 6L, but later required venturi mask with 8L oxygen. He was found to be COVID positive. He underwent CTA that was negative for PE. Patient had elevated troponin first 55, repeat 73. Cardiology saw patient and thought it was likely demand ischemia and no need for additional intervention. Patient was admitted for medicine for additional management.    ASSESSMENT / PLAN: Patient is a 91 y.o. with a PMH of COPD, HTN, PVD, DM type II, CKD who was admitted on 11/1 with COVID-19 pneumonia. COVID pneumonia Baseline 6L, requiring 8L venturi on exam. Will treat with dexamethasone and remdesivir due to high risk of decompensation.  Plan: - dexamethasone 6 mg daily - remdesivir - daily CBC and CMP - oxygen to maintain sats 88-92% - continuous pulse ox Elevated troponin:  Troponin 55, repeat 73 on admission. EKG with no ST changes. Likely demand ischemia due to poor oxygenation.   - repeat troponin Progress Note 11.8.21:  DISCHARGED  DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 91 y.o. male who presented with increased SOB  found to be COVID 19 positive on date 11/1/21. CXR showed bibasilar opacities in LLL. He was treated with decadron, full course of remdesivir and diuresed with Lasix. He did require increased oxygen from his home requirements of 6L up to 12L venturi mask. Additionally, blood cultures were 1/2 positive for strep mitis/strep oralis. He was managed with IV abx and transitioned to augmentin prior to discharge. With diuresis and treatment, he improved both clinically and in lab findings. They were discharged home in stable condition back to his baseline of 6L to complete decadron course and antibiotic regimen Outcome Summary: VSS on 6L NC. D/c instructions and wound supplies sent with patient. D/c today. Pt. picked up by niece and left with home O2.

I was on methotrexate and Actemra for rhematoid arthritis with Pfizer vaccines.  With the second Pfizer dose, my right hand swelled two days later with painfull itchy zoster-like lesions on the back of my hand.  There was resolution in a week.  For this reason, I chose Moderna for my third vaccination off of all immunosuppressants. Two days after the Moderna shot, I woke up with flu-like symproms, a dry cough and tachypnea. Three days later, the cough and tachypnea got worse.  I also developed precordial chest pain and a bout of near syncope with a systolic BP of 70.  The hypotension lasted about an hour.  On day #4, I woke up with worse non-radiating heart pain with dyspnea.  My SpO2 was 75% and I called Emergency. Additional information for Item 18: There was never any fever.  The rescue squad called in an elevation of my ST segments in V2 and V3, then gave me aspirin.  In the ER, I received SoluMedrol 125 mg IV.  My chest pain improved in 6 hours.  My cardiologist called me to stop taking dofetilide since my QT interval was >500 and that my troponins were elevated but not high enough to suspect a heart attack.   CXR in the ER showed bilateral infiltrates with ground glass appearance.  Since the D-dimer was elevated, a chest CTA was done.  There was no pulmonary emboli, but ground glass infiltrates were noted.  Doxycycline was started IV since WBC's showed a marked shift to the left.  I also received high flow nasal O2 and later heparin. Later that day, I was transfered to an isolation room.  The COVID nasal swab was done in the ER and then on the floor a few days later; both were negative. On Sept 13, I went into atrial fibrillation.  Dofetilide was restarted and my rhythm converted to NSR.  On 9/14, an echocardiogram showed an ejection fraction of 60% and a pericardial effusion was not seen.  Prednisone 20 mg qd was started on the 15th to be continued for five days with a rapid taper.  I was off of O2 on that day with a SpO2 in the 90's.  On September 16 (the day of discharge) a 6 minute walk test was performed.  The SpO2 dropped into the low 80's, and the pulse went up to 135 BPM.  I also experienced some chest discomfort.  On my own, I gave myself an injection of anakinra.  I was discharged with an oxygen concentrator.  I continued doxycycline for two weeks. Anakinra daily injections were continued for 10 days, then Actemra (tocilizumab) was resumed.  Five days after discharge, I no longer had tachycardia or dyspnea with brisk walking.  I still have an occasional dry cough which does not interfere with sleep.  A high resolution CT of my chest is ordered for November 17th with follow-up with my pulmonologist.  I do have a history of myopericarditis following an ablation for atrial fibrillation in 2016.  The ablation lead to hemorrhagic tamponade and a pericardial window to drain 1100 cc of blood.  The pericarditis was treated with prednisone and colchicine.  Seronegative rheumatoid arthritis involving the hands and heart was diagnosed shortly thereafter.  Methotrexate did not control the arthritis.  As an immunologist, I researched treatment for rheumatoid pericarditis and found anakinra.  The effect was remarkable, and it was continued for two years.  There were occasional breakthroughs with high exertion cardio activities requiring resumption of anakinra.  I kept two weeks of treatment  "just in case".   I brought one week of anakinra with me in the ambulance and left it in the hospital refrigerator.

It was reported to this writer that RN who was assisting in supervising patients in the post-vaccination observation area responded while patient was seated and assessed that he was pale and drowsy. RN reported she gave the patient apple juice. Shortly after the patient stated that he felt better and was escorted by RN with mother present to private medical cot area to lie down. This writer immediately responded to the medical incident to support clinical staff and observed the patient was stable but still pale. RN took serial vitals for patient that were within defined limits. Patient was given more apple juice and said he felt better at 04:09pm and told his mother with clinical staff present that he only had a small snack after school and 1 hour before his mother had picked him up from school. Patient also stated that when clinical staff in post-observation area began talking again about possible vaccine side effects with mother that patient said he got scared and anxious. After 10 minutes of resting on the medical cot with mother and RN staff present and another round of stable vital signs noted by RNs, patient stated he felt good and slowly stood up at the side of the cot. Patient denied any dizziness or feelings of weakness. Patient skin color returned with defined limits, no paleness noted. Patient ambulated in the care of his mother who was driving them both home at that time out of the clinic without any issues or adventitious findings at 04:21pm.
LAB_DATA: unknown, no tests performed by clinical staff present at vaccination site the day of incident 11/08/2021.

On an unknown date in September 2014 (reported as within 2 weeks), the patient felt as though as he was on fire (the feeling of being on fire started on the back of the patient's legs), patient became allergic to many foods like milk, developed nerve damage, rash, hives and blisters.Multiple blood test and lung rays were performed (result not provided).       The outcome of nerve damage, became allergic to many foods like milk, felt as though i was on fire, rash, hives and blisters was reported as not recovered.        Follow up information was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation. No information was provided regarding the patient's (pt's) medical history, drug reactions, concurrent conditions. On an unknown date, in or around May 2014 (conflicting information with previously reported, start date updated according to the newly provided information), the pt was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, anatomical location, lot # and expiration date were not specified in the follow up) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt suffered shingles. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the pt's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the pt suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the vaccine, the pt suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of shingles was considered to be not recovered/not resolved. The reporter considered the event of shingles to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  The previously reported events of felt as though he was on fire, rash, and blisters were removed, as symptoms of shingles.  The event of herpes zoster was considered to be disabling.
CUR_ILL: Blood pressure abnormal; Routine health maintenance; Thyroid disorder

The patient's past medical history included: multigravida, and concurrent conditions included: non tobacco user, and non alcohol user, and other pre-existing medical conditions included: patient had no history of exposure to drugs for recreational use. Patient Body Mass Index(BMI) was 26.85. Her obstetrical history included four previous pregnancies, of which one resulted in live newborn and two ended with miscarriage. The patient initiated treatment with Covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, intramuscular, batch number: 1802070, expiry: unknown) dose was not reported, frequency time 1 total was administered on 06-MAR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. SYMPTOM_TEXT: ACUTE MOTOR-SENSORY AXONAL NEUROPATHY; CERVICAL STENOSIS; HYPOXIA; SYMPTOMATIC BRADYCARDIA; HOARSENESS; LIGHTHEADEDNESS; This spontaneous report was received from literature: A Rare Variant of Guillain-Barre Syndrome Following Ad26.COV2.S Vaccination. This report concerned a 49 year old female of white (Caucasian) race and unspecified ethnicity.  The objective of this study is to describe a rare variant of GBS with a temporal relation to the Ad26.COV2.S. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's concurrent conditions included: neurofibromatosis type 1, hypothyroidism, and multiple vitamin deficiencies and the patient was healthy. The patient's history was negative for any recent illnesses, changes to medications or lifestyle, domestic or international travel or exposure to any known sick contacts. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: Unknown and expiry: UNKNOWN) dose, start therapy date were not reported,1 total administered for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported and has been requested. No concomitant medications were reported. It was reported that on an unspecified date the patient was presented to her primary care physician with new-onset numbness in her extremities for a duration of one day. She experienced reduced tactile sensation and numbness in her right upper extremity, extending from the elbow into her hand and bilateral lower extremities from her knees through her feet. She had associated headache with pain to palpation across her forehead, lightheadedness, and aching lumbar pain of four days duration. The patient received the vaccine five days prior to the onset of her symptoms. Later due to acute neurological involvement of her multiple extremities with reduced tactile sensation, the patient was directed immediately to the emergency department for further evaluation. During the initial emergency department evaluation, the patient endorsed difficulty walking and holding objects in addition to the previously reported symptoms. These difficulties were thought to be secondary to altered sensation rather than resulting from musculoskeletal weakness. Physical exam revealed orbital, jaw, and neck pain to palpation. The patient was afebrile, severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) negative, and showed no signs of infection or electrolyte abnormality on initial complete blood count (CBC), comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP), and urinalysis (UA). Thyroid-stimulating hormone, free thyroxine, and muscle-specific kinase antibodies were within normal limits. The only abnormal blood work seen was an equivocal B12 level of 187 ng/L (normal 180-914 ng/L). She also underwent an MRI of her brain and cervical spine for concerns of multiple sclerosis given her multiple neurologic symptoms. Brain MRI revealed small punctate foci inconsistent with multiple sclerosis or acute neurologic findings. Due to equivocal B12 levels and non-specific MRI findings, the patient was given a B12 injection and discharged to her home with instructions for outpatient follow-up with neurology. It was also reported that the patient returned to the emergency department next day with worsening generalized weakness and paresthesia. The patient also noted new hoarseness and dysphagia, thoracic back pain, and urinary incontinence that had all developed within the 16 hours since her emergency department (ED) discharge. In ED (emergency department) triage, the patient collapsed to the floor without loss of consciousness or seizure activities. She was afebrile, hypertensive to 171/98, and hypoxic with oxygen saturation in the mid-80s.Her physical exam was positive for symmetric weakness in bilateral lower extremities. A CT (Computed Tomography) angiogram of the chest was ordered for concerns of a developing aortic dissection, which was unremarkable. Additional imaging was then ordered, with an MRI of the brain, which showed moderate cervical stenosis. MRI of the thoracic and lumbar spine was also conducted but was otherwise unremarkable. Her lumbar puncture revealed elevated albumin (normal less than 27.0 mg/dL) and IgG (normal less than 8.1 mg/dL) without signs of meningitis or multiple sclerosis and the patient was admitted to the medical intensive care unit (MICU) due to her rapidly progressing neurological symptoms. The patient's physical examination was notable for bilateral extraocular muscles weakness, decreased pinprick sensation in all four extremities, with preserved temperature and vibratory sensation, 4 out of 5 strengths in the right upper extremity, bilateral proximal lower extremities, and bilateral finger flexion, with preserved 5 out of 5 strengths in the left upper extremity. Additionally, reflexes were tested and showed 1plus in bilateral biceps and brachioradialis and absent at the bilateral patella and achilles. By hospital day 4, the patient became almost quadriplegic, along with bilateral facial nerve paralysis and a weak gag reflex. She required bilevel positive airway pressure (BiPAP) initially and eventually intubation. Given her rapid neurological decompensation, with sensory symptoms with negative workup and recent history of vaccination, clinically, neurology suspected this was a rare variant of GBS called acute motor and sensory axonal neuropathy (AMSAN). She was started on intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG). On hospital day 13, she remained intubated without significant improvement despite four days of IVIG. She developed symptomatic bradycardia that required pacemaker placement. On hospital days 23-32, the patient received a course of plasmapheresis, due to lack of clinical improvement, and a tracheostomy. On hospital days 33-54, the patient underwent physical rehab and ventilatory weaning at Select Hospital. On hospital days 54-63, the patient was readmitted by neurology for a second round of plasmapheresis and an additional dose of IVIG. Following these treatments, she had gradual improvement in her weakness. On hospital day 64, the patient was transferred back to hospital. The Author concluded that the unique presentation of the rare variant of GBS, AMSAN, can make a prompt diagnosis challenging and difficult. When evaluating patients with progressive paralysis with and without neuropathy, GBS should remain in the differential, even if patients do not follow exactly the characteristic stocking and glove pattern. Early involvement of the neurology team in suspected cases may help diagnose patients presenting with some of the unique neurological features, ultimately allowing for quicker intervention. SYMPTOM_TEXT: inflammation of optic nerve/ optic neuritis; Aphasia/Stroke like aphasia; Numbness in my right arm; Slurred speech; maybe a stroke; numbness in face; Autoimmune disease called MOG; blurred vision; losing vision in left eye; Swelling on my retina; Seizure; Status migrainosus/persistent migraine; Numbness in my right arm,; Slurred speech; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of APHASIA (Aphasia/Stroke like aphasia), HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm), the second episode of DYSARTHRIA (Slurred speech), CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (maybe a stroke), OPTIC NEURITIS (inflammation of optic nerve/ optic neuritis), SEIZURE (Seizure), STATUS MIGRAINOSUS (Status migrainosus/persistent migraine), RETINAL OEDEMA (Swelling on my retina) and AUTOIMMUNE DISORDER (Autoimmune disease called MOG) in a 32-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 043L20A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     Concurrent medical conditions included Epilepsy (Epilepsy stable since age 7.) since 1995. Concomitant products included LEVETIRACETAM (KEPPRA [LEVETIRACETAM]) from 2015 to an unknown date for Seizures.   On 16-Jan-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form. On 12-Feb-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 04-Aug-2021, the patient experienced STATUS MIGRAINOSUS (Status migrainosus/persistent migraine) (seriousness criterion medically significant), HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm,) and the first episode of DYSARTHRIA (Slurred speech). On 24-Aug-2021, the patient experienced APHASIA (Aphasia/Stroke like aphasia) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant), HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), the second episode of DYSARTHRIA (Slurred speech) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant) and CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (maybe a stroke) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant). On 27-Aug-2021, the patient experienced SEIZURE (Seizure) (seriousness criterion medically significant). On 01-Sep-2021, the patient experienced RETINAL OEDEMA (Swelling on my retina) (seriousness criterion medically significant), VISION BLURRED (blurred vision ) and VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (losing vision in left eye). On 05-Oct-2021, the patient experienced OPTIC NEURITIS (inflammation of optic nerve/ optic neuritis) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant). In October 2021, the patient experienced AUTOIMMUNE DISORDER (Autoimmune disease called MOG) (seriousness criterion medically significant). On an unknown date, the patient experienced HYPOAESTHESIA (numbness in face). The patient was hospitalized from 24-Aug-2021 to 26-Aug-2021 due to APHASIA, CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT, DYSARTHRIA and HYPOAESTHESIA. The patient was treated with TOTAL PARENTERAL NUTRITION INJECTION (25) in August 2021 at an unspecified dose and frequency and KETOROLAC TROMETHAMINE (TORADOL) (intravenous) in August 2021 at a dose of IV Toradol. On 27-Aug-2021, SEIZURE (Seizure) had resolved. On 10-Sep-2021, APHASIA (Aphasia/Stroke like aphasia) had resolved with sequelae. At the time of the report, HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm), the last episode of DYSARTHRIA (Slurred speech), CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (maybe a stroke), OPTIC NEURITIS (inflammation of optic nerve/ optic neuritis), RETINAL OEDEMA (Swelling on my retina), AUTOIMMUNE DISORDER (Autoimmune disease called MOG), VISION BLURRED (blurred vision ), HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm,), VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (losing vision in left eye) and HYPOAESTHESIA (numbness in face) outcome was unknown and STATUS MIGRAINOSUS (Status migrainosus/persistent migraine) had not resolved.      DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS (normal ranges are provided in parenthesis if available): On 04-Aug-2021, Computerised tomogram: normal (normal) Normal. On 04-Aug-2021, Magnetic resonance imaging: normal (normal) Normal. On 24-Aug-2021, Computerised tomogram: normal (normal) Normal. On 24-Aug-2021, Magnetic resonance imaging: normal (normal) Normal. On 05-Oct-2021, Magnetic resonance imaging head: abnormal (abnormal) discovered 22mm of inflammation of my optic nerve.     For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown), the reporter considered APHASIA (Aphasia/Stroke like aphasia), SEIZURE (Seizure) and STATUS MIGRAINOSUS (Status migrainosus/persistent migraine) to be possibly related. No further causality assessments were provided for HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm), DYSARTHRIA (Slurred speech), CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (maybe a stroke), OPTIC NEURITIS (inflammation of optic nerve/ optic neuritis), RETINAL OEDEMA (Swelling on my retina), AUTOIMMUNE DISORDER (Autoimmune disease called MOG), VISION BLURRED (blurred vision ), HYPOAESTHESIA (Numbness in my right arm,), DYSARTHRIA (Slurred speech), VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (losing vision in left eye) and HYPOAESTHESIA (numbness in face).    The patient started having Seizures recently and dosage for Epilepsy medicine increased to 1500 mg from 1000 mg.  In Aug-2021, the patient had multiple visits to ER, 6 months after final vaccination.  The patient had no symptoms immediately after vaccination, but she started noticing the change in her body (being able to grasp, numbness in face) later.  On 04-Aug-2021, the patient was treated with IV Toradol.  On 24-Aug-2021, the patient was treated with treated TPN.  On 27-Aug-2021, the patient had Seizure and taken to Urgent care where they gave her IV fluids. After that incident, the patient noticed loss of vision in her left eye.   On 01-Sep-2021, the patient consulted Ophthalmologist as she began losing vision in her left eye and had blurred vision. He found swelling on her retina. Ophthalmologist identified swelling of her optic nerve.   On 05-Oct-2021, the patient saw the neuro ophthalmologist ran a field test and optic nerve tests. The patient underwent a lumbar puncture test, results were not provided.  On 05-Oct-2021, the patient was hospitalized for 7 days. The patient received plasmapheresis and IV steroids treatment.   Upon discharge, the patient received diagnosis of optic neuritis and autoimmune disease of MOG.  The patient stated that all things were triggered by immune response and now, she would have to be monitored for flare.  This case concerns a 32 year-old female patient with history of epilepsy, who experienced the unexpected serious events of Seizure, Status migrainosus, Retinal oedema, Optic neuritis, Autoimmune disorder, and Cerebrovascular accident. Details of the events, diagnostic criteria, and clinical course were not provided.The patient's history of epilepsy likely contributed to the event of Seizure. The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA-1273 vaccine is not affected by this report.   This case was linked to MOD-2021-363446 (Patient Link).
