SYMPTOM_TEXT: Aphthous ulcer of the vagina, fever, fatigue, myalgias and sores in vaginal area; This is a spontaneous report based on unpublished manuscript from a contactable physician.   A 16-year-old non-sexually active female presented to the pediatric gynecology clinic with vaginal pain. Six days prior she had received her second dose of the Pfizer BioNTech (BNT162b2) COVID-19 vaccine. Within 24 hours of receiving the vaccine, she developed fever, fatigue, myalgias and sores in her vaginal area. Over the next 2 days, right sided lesions in her vaginal area coalesced and became more painful. She presented to urgent care with a fever of 105 degrees Fahrenheit where she was diagnosed with a Bartholin gland abscess and prescribed amoxicillin-clavulanate. Despite antibiotic therapy, her symptoms continued to worsen prompting her to return to clinic two days later. By this point, the lesions were covered in exudate with a necrotic, ring-like border. Gynecology was consulted and recommended assessment for likely Lipschutz ulcers. In gynecology clinic, the patient's lesions were exquisitely painful, resulting in difficulty with urination, defecation, and walking. She had no respiratory symptoms and no known COVID-19 exposures. Her medical history was significant for several congenital conditions requiring corrective surgeries including soft palate cleft, club foot, syndactyly of her left foot and congenital hearing impairment in the right ear. Additionally, the patient reported a history of recurrent oral ulcerations, but no previous history of genital ulcerations. Her family history was notable for severe canker sores in her father and uncle requiring medical intervention and hospitalization. The patient denied any history of sexual activity. On exam, the patient was afebrile and in no acute distress. Her genitourinary exam was significant for an ulcerated lesion with adherent yellow and grey fibrinous exudate on the right labia minora measuring 3 cm x 2 cm. The ulcer was well-demarcated with a necrotic appearing border. Desquamation was observed of the surrounding tissue and the posterior fourchette. The affected right labia was markedly swollen in comparison to the left. Laboratory evaluation was negative for SARS-COV-2 RNA by anterior nares swab. Viral polymerase chain reaction testing of the vulvar lesion was negative for herpes simplex virus (HSV) 1 and 2 as well as serum testing for HSV 1 and 2 antibodies. Epstein Barr nuclear antigen (EBNA) antibodies were present, indicating prior infection with EBV. Testing for CMV, syphilis (RPR), and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) were negative. Fluorescent antinuclear antibody screen was negative. Clinical history and genital examination findings were consistent with vulvar aphthous ulcers in association with influenza-like symptoms following Pfizer BioNTech (BNT162b2) COVID-19 vaccination. The patient was prescribed topical clobetasol 0.05% ointment and instructed to apply to the affected area twice daily for 14 days. Her pain management regimen included ibuprofen and acetaminophen as needed, as well as topical lidocaine gel. She was started on norethindrone 5 mg orally daily for menstrual suppression while her ulcerations were healing. She presented for follow up two weeks later and reported improvement in her symptoms, although she was experiencing sensitivity with vulvar manipulation and pain with urination. The ulcerated lesion was noted to be resolving along the medial aspect of the right vaginal introitus. Vulvar edema had resolved. She reported the appearance of an oral ulcer several days prior and physical exam was consistent with aphthous ulcer on the inner aspect of her lower lip. Patient was referred to rheumatology in light of her recurrent oral aphthous ulcers, vulvar ulcer and family history of oral ulcerations. The case was submitted to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) due to the temporal relationship with COVID vaccine administration.  Summary and Conclusions This is the first case report to describe a potential relationship between the development of vulvar aphthous ulcers and COVID-19 vaccination. Our patient had typical clinical features of aphthous ulcer including an influenza-like prodrome and characteristic dermatologic manifestations which occurred after receiving the Pfizer COVID vaccine.  The temporal relationship of our patient's symptoms to Pfizer BioNTech (BNT162b2) vaccination in the context of a negative test for SARS-COV-RNA, as well as other infectious etiologies, suggest that her systemic symptoms and vulvar aphthous ulcer may have occurred secondary to an immune response precipitated by the vaccine. However, there are several other factors in this patient, including evidence of past infection with EBV and medical and family history of recurrent oral ulcers, which potentially contributed to their presentation.  This case suggests that vulvar aphthous ulcers may be precipitated by vaccination, however, further research is required to establish a causal relationship. One proposed mechanism for study is to investigate how the immune system's response to vaccination recapitulates the pro-inflammatory response associated with vulvar aphthous ulcers secondary to viral illness.  Event occurred in a country different from that of the reporter.  This may be a duplicate if the reporter also submitted directly to his/her local agency.  Follow-up attempts are completed. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 1-2 hours after I received my third shot which was my booster shot of Pfizer I began quickly to feel body aches and developed a rather high fever. I had been previously feeling fine. My first shot I had no side effects other than sore Covid arm, my second shot I was bed ridden for a few days with similar side effects as expected (everyone says the second shot makes you feel sick) but this one the booster shot, I am still currently experiencing severe body aches and a rather high fever with chills over 24 hours later. I ended up having to be sent home from work because it was so bad. Others I know who had their third booster Shot by Pfizer had no side effects. Also at the time of my injection for my third booster shot I ended up bleeding pools of blood from the injection site for over an hour even with a bandaid on and some pressure from a tissue. I have no known bleeding problems and previously from shots I have never bled more or longer than the slight normal amount. I?m also extremely cautious during this entire pandemic even to this day, I don?t surround myself with people from other households without seeing a produced negative Covid test from them and I wear my mask and disposable gloves EVERYWHERE. I even sanitize after every small thing outside of my home so I am notoriously cautious. So this leads to some issue from my booster shot and not anything else.

First and second shot was very sick/felt like my head was going to explode for a few days after second shot along with extreme shacking and cold feeling that started app 12 hours after shot#2 and lasted a week. Tired all the time and extreme brain fog that is still here and has not stopped some days are better than others but some days are really bad. will start to feel better than without any cause I feel really bad. I try to work through it but many times it is debilitating and extreme frustration. Then in October admitted my self into emergency my heart felt like it was going to explode and was all over the place which the ekg recorded was given a shot of Protonin (if I remember properly) . they were going to give me a second shot and my heart went back to normal. I have not seen a cardiologist  as of  yet.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to contrast when I had an MRI done

Around 12:30 am on 10/24/21 I started to have very bad chills and pain in my entire left arm. Especially the joints. I started experiencing body aches as well. Around 1:30 am on 10/24/21, I started having severe chest pain. There was a stabbing sensation going in through my heart out to my shoulder blade. The pain radiated from my heart into my left collar bone, armpit, shoulder and jaw. There was a loss of grip strength in my left hand and I had a very bad headache. Around 5:30am I got very nauseous and started to vomit. Around 8:00 am I noticed swelling in my left armpit. The flu like symptoms only lasted 24 hours, but the chest pain continued. I went to ED on 10/26/21 and they said it was muscular. I went to Cardiologist on 11/1 and they said the vaccine most likely triggered my pericarditis.  I did also receive my flu vaccine on 10/23/21 (in right arm). I did not add it because I did not know which one it was.
LAB_DATA: EKG, bloodwork and x-rays done on 10/26. All looked normal except for EKG. T waves inverted showing potential pericarditis.

Hospitalized 10/26/2021; COVID-19 positive 10/27/2021, fully vaccinated  BRIEF OVERVIEW: Discharge Provider: DOCTOR Primary Care Physician at Discharge: DOCTOR Admission Date: 10/26/2021 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Septic shock   HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 60 year old male with PMH of HTN, HLD, DMII, super morbid obesity who initially presented to outside hospital with a 2-3 day history of right groin rash and found to have necrotizing fascitis. Patient underwent his initial debridement at outside hospital prior to transferring to Butterworth SICU. Of note, patient was hypoxic prior to intubation and found to have COVID-19 pneumonia which was treated with steroids and Remdesivir. Patient was intubated and sedated upon transfer and had pressor requirements due to septic shock from the necrotizing fascitis. Patient underwent IV abx therapy, resuscitation with fluids and pressors, and ventilator support. Patient underwent a second debridement for source control the following day. Patient's ICU course was also complicated by Diabetic ketoacidosis for which he was on endotool with DGMS following, AKI, and SVT with RVR. During his ICU course, source control was obtained from his infection, however patient's respiratory status continued to decline with ARDS. Patient on high ventilator requirements of 90-100% Fi02 with hypercarbia due to large body habitus with chest wall restrction, COVID-19, and volume overload due to resuscitation for septic shock. Patient was paralyzed during his course to assist with ventilation however this did not improve his respiratory status. Pulmonary critical care was consulted however patient not a candidate for ECMO given his BMI. Discussion was held with family (sister) on 10/31/21 given poor prognosis even with aggressive therapy. Comfort care was ultimately decided upon per family. Paralyzation was stopped and patient was subsequently extubated and expired on 10/31/2021 at 1354

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Started to feel dizzy with ringing in my ears and trouble focusing on work around 10am around 10:45 my face started to feel numb and I felt like I was going to pass out. Laid my head down for a bit and then called my PCP's office. While talking to the nurse, my speech was slurred and my tongue and the roof of my mouth started to feel numb. she advised me to take Benadryl and call 911. I took Benadryl called 911 they sent out EMS and they advised me that I was just injected with a live virus and this was the side effect of having COVID. That made no sense to me, she then instructed me to take DayQuil for the effects of having COVID. I told the EMT that I was not feeling like I had the flu I felt out of it and numb. She checked my vitals and lungs and said everything was good and that they could transport me to the Hospital ED but they were full and I would just be sitting there and it would be best to rest in my home. That if the Benadryl wore off or if things got worse, to go to urgent care. I slept and when I woke up the facial numbness was less and my tongue and mouth no longer felt numb. I was dizzy and my ears were still ringing and disoriented the entire day. The next day I was extremely tired and started to having coughing with chest pain when I would cough and by that evening I was having joint pain everywhere. Today I feel better, still have the coughing with chest pain. Following up with my PCP at 9:20am 11/04/21.

The thing that prompted me to go to the doctor was that Monday morning, I was unable to lift my arm. I had fever and chills Saturday night and my arm started hurting Saturday night and was quite painful on Sunday and by Monday the pain was radiating to my under arm. I called the clinic on Monday and talked to triage nurse. She said they were seeing this with patients who had the booster. She scheduled me an appt for Tuesday in case it wasn't better. I went in to make sure everything was okay. She said I had lymphadenopathy in that arm where the shot was. It was probably related to the vaccine, she said. She gave me some gentle exercises to do so that I would move my shoulder. I opted to not take any prescription medicine. She had me take 800 mg of Ibuprofen every 8 hours. She asked me to get back in touch with her by Thursday. I was still having pain on Thursday, so she decided that I stay on the Advil for another day. It is still a little sore now, but I have full movement back now so I'm not nearly as worried about it. Note: I do not know for sure what brand of flu vaccine that I received that day - it was the flu vaccine that everyone for the whole company received.

A week after taking the first vaccine, my muscles have been sporadically spasming. The spasms have varied in severity, but on more than one occasion have been severe enough to require me to fall straight down to the floor in order to find a position which was not painful and remain in that spot for a couple of minutes before being able to move properly again. The side effects began with a low-grade fever and general achiness all over the body. This progressed to a high fever (~103.5 degrees F) with chills and extreme achiness. The fever was controlled with over-the-counter medication, but continued to spike up with the same intensity over the following 48-72 hours when left untreated. The injection site, including the left arm and armpit, were sore and achy over the next 96 hours. Some swelling in the lymph nodes occurred during the affected period, particularly in the left armpit and under the left-side jaw. There was achiness and soreness through the limbs, accompanied by a "restless legs"-type feeling occasionally in the legs. Headache was present on-and-off for 96 hours after the effects onset, with concentrated pain in the neck and brow area. Some vomiting and digestive upset occurred only in the first 24 hours after the injection. Other minor side effects include a cold feeling in the left side hand and fingertips, mild dizziness, and mild nasal congestion. Overall, the side effects were intense, but were generally flu-like and presented no discernable threat to safety or wellbeing.
PRIOR_VAX: Similar reaction to Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine dose #2 (administered 2/16/2021, lot number EN6200)

6/16/21:  3 circular lesions.  The most distal one in particular has an erythematous, raised, crusted border with some central clearing.  The others are more diffusely erythematous with an irregular border and satellite lesions.  He has 1 main lesion on the proximal right lower leg as well with similar appearance.  The lesions are not blanchable. Prescribed antifungal cream - ketoconazole (NIZORAL) 2 % cream . Did not work. Returned to clinic 1 week later.   6/25/21:  Patient was seen by Dr. on 6/16, at which time he presented for evaluation of new lesions emerging on his lower legs.  He had some associated pruritus and discomfort with these spots.  No provoking factors were identified.  On exam, he was noted to be mildly hypertensive to 143/94, with 3 circular lesions on the left lower leg which had central clearing and raised, crusted borders.  Plan was put in place for the patient to be treated with topical antifungal cream, with baseline labs obtained including a CBC, creatinine and urinalysis.  All of this was overall unremarkable.  Plans were then made for him to return today for follow-up of his blood pressure and assessment of the rash after a short course of topical antifungals.   Today, patient reports that the rash on his anterior shins is largely unchanged and continues to be pruritic from time to time, worsened with contact with hot water.  No improvement has been noted since starting the antifungal cream.     His blood pressure continues to be elevated today.  In speaking with him, he actually does have some exertional shortness of breath from time to time, though no associated diaphoresis or chest pain.  He endorses no exertional headaches or vision changes.  6/25/21:  66-year-old male presenting with EMS from home for chest pain.  Onset of pain was around 6:00 p.m. after he had finished eating dinner.  His pain is severe, sharp, located in the right lower chest, pleuritic and not associated with exertion.  He has never had a pain like this before.  It does not radiate.  He denies cough or significant shortness of breath but states that he is not taking deep breath because it exacerbates the pain.  No fever.  No known recent trauma.  He has been found to have elevated blood pressure recently but has not been started on medications.  He states he has also had elevated cholesterol.  His father had a heart attack when he was in his 40s.  The patient does not have any known coronary artery disease.  He is a current smoker.  No history of PE or DVT.  No cancer.  No recent surgery or immobilization.  No hemoptysis.  No leg swelling or pain.  He is not anticoagulated.  He has had a rash on his shins since April. Regular rhythm and normal heart sounds.  Tachycardia present.  Pulses are strong.  Capillary refill: takes less than 3 seconds, Pulmonary/Chest: Breath sounds normal. Tachypnea noted. He has no wheezes. He has no rales. Abdominal: Soft. There is no abdominal tenderness. Musculoskeletal:        General: No edema (No lower extremity edema).     Cervical back: Normal range of motion. Neurological: Alert. He is not disoriented. Skin: Skin is warm and dry.  He has erythematous nonblanching rash on bilateral shins.  Psychiatric: Behavior is normal.   Multiple Subsegmental Pulmonary Embolism Without Acute Cor Pulmonale
LAB_DATA: Etiology of PE not yet clear; no known prolonged travel, no recent surgery. Malignancy is a possibility. In July 2021 he had one dose of Pfizer vaccine and within 15 minutes he felt 'impending doom', and then heart racing, got tunnel vision, chest pressure, throat constriction and 'felt like he was going to die' and vitals checked by nurse and discharged once he reported to nurse that he felt better a half hour later even though he didn't feel back to baseline.  He was fatigued.  He went home and the second day felt continued fatigue, heart palpitations and SOB, and nausea, chills, fever. The third day, 7/8/21 he started noticing widely fluctuating HR 52 at baseline rose to HR 110 and felt SOB , chest tight and throat tightness and went to ER who did a workup that was inconclusive.  He has had intermittent palpitations since and during workout he is getting SOB that is unusual.  This is a previously active and athletic individual.  Since the vaccine, he has a knot in his throat and feels reflux more (reflux exacerbated from his baseline but stable on Omeprazole now), feels palpitations and tachypnea, SOB with exertion such as weights, and progressively worsening SOB with even moderate intensity walking and with prolonged mask wearing.  This SOB with mask had not occurred pre-vaccine.   Pt has not gone back to the gym since workup including seeing a cardiologist and pulmonologist.   He had a second ER visit on 8/5/21 for this.   Cardiologist ordered Echo and EST and results normal, despite SOB. Holter monitor done but inconclusive with one episode of HR 120. Pt has had an episode of elevated HR 120 with some irregularity on it , and cardiologist ordered CT and MRI and if negative, will have another round of strength training while Holter.  Pt reports strength training at gym resulted in HR fluctuating from 100 down to 42 suddenly on fit bit and he was scared and stopped.  Pulmonologist is ordering PFT and apnea test next.  I performed a spirometry with FEV1 of 72% which is abnormal.  As an allergist, I ordered skin testing to Peg 3350 containing medications today and it was positive.   Peg 3350 is in Miralax and DepoMedrol and is also in the MRNA COVID vaccines by Pfizer.    In summary, Patient is likely one of the rare true IgE mediated PEG - allergic patients who had anaphylaxis to his Pfizer vaccine #1.   What is unusual is his chronic and debilitating respiratory and cardiac abnormalities that continued after his anaphylactic episode.
LAB_DATA: Cardiologist ordered Echo and EST and results normal. Spirometry with FEV1 of 72% which is abnormal.  Skin testing to Peg 3350 containing medications was positive.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came to pharmacy for first moderna COVID vaccine. Patient was checked in and screened by technician. He stated he felt dizzy this morning but that is not unusual. temp was normal and no other issues stated by patient. Patient was given vaccination by pharmacist. She reported he bled through 2 bandaids. She then switched out with me due to her lunch break. I came into the room to make sure he was ok because she said it was more blood than ususal and when I entered the patient was brow was beading with a small amount of sweat. I asked the patient if they were feeling ok. He stated he felt dizzy or light headed and maybe a little nauseous. I asked if he had eaten that day. He stated he had, I asked if he had health conditions. The patient stated they had high blood pressure. I asked if they had taken their medications that day and he stated he had taken them. I asked if I could take his blood pressure and he agreed. His blood pressure was great 135/72 heart rate 74. I asked him to keep sitting in the vaccine room as he had more sweat on his forehead now and let him know he could remove his mask if he was having difficulty breathing. He said he thought he might be and removed it. He said he felt nauseous again so I put a trash can in front of him and offered some water. He said he wanted water so technician went and got him some water. I stepped out of the room for a quick consult and asked another tech to make sure to watch the patient. If he fell immediatley let me know. I finished the consult and was heading back to the room when I heard vomiting so I remained outside but could see him through the glass. He continued to vomit and was on the floor on his knees. Another consult came to the window so I stepped up to the consult as I finished I heard a sound from the vaccination room and ran to look and the patient was now on the floor on his side lying limp. I asked can you breathe can you breathe? He did not response. His eyes were open though. His lips looked a little purple/blue and I placed my hand in front of his mouth. I told him I was going to administer an epipen if he can't breathe and he did not respond. I gave the epipen and he became more responsive and was answering questions with one word or blinking.  When going to grab the epipen I told my technician to call code White and emergency and we alerted staff. EMS came and picked up patient

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was biking home from work (which I usually do 1-3 times per week) and about 3-5 minutes into the ride I started feeling worse than I usually do biking (more short of breath, more tired, more chest tightness, harder to breathe, a lot of mucus in my throat, much more painful in my throat). At about 15 minutes in I was really coughing a lot and it felt very hard to breathe and I had a very sharp pain in my throat, like the muscle was spasming. The ride was about 20-30 min. I was alternating between coughing and gasping for air when I got home. I laid down but that made it harder to breathe so I stood back up. It was difficult to talk because I couldn't get enough air. I thought maybe I had developed exercise-induced asthma since it was the first time it was colder out so I went to the urgent care who sent me to the ER. I started feeling anxious and I was hyperventilating, which I think made me feel dizzy and tingly in my hands and legs. By the time I was there at the ER, I had started to feel better, and by the time I was admitted I felt completely better except for some lingering chest tightness and sore throat which I think was from the coughing - that lasted about 48 hours. Now I feel completely better, but I haven't tried biking again so I'm not sure if this is something that would happen again.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalized 10/30/2021; COVID-19 positive 10/26/2021; fully vaccinated  BRIEF OVERVIEW: Admission Date: 10/30/2021 Discharge Date: 11/02/2021 Presenting Problem: COVID-19 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: HOSPITAL COURSE: This patient is a 70 yo female with past medical history of heart transplant 3/21/19, chronic immunosuppression, hx neutropenia and CMV viremia, OSA on CPAP, hx TIA, right hip OA s/p arthroplasty Aug 2021 and prior gastric bypass who was diagnosed with COVID 19 on 10/26, received monoclonal antibodies but required admission on 10/30/21 for worsened symptoms.  She reported fatigue, cough and decreased appetite.  She did not have any difficulty keeping her transplant medications down. Upon presentation she was mildly hypoxemic and her chest x-ray appearances of normal.  There was some question of volume overload since her BNP was elevated at 7000. She was given a dose of Lasix, but a repeat chest x-ray was no better.  However echocardiogram showed small IVC.  Her abnormal chest x-ray was thought to be more related to COVID than volume overload. She was placed on 2 L supplemental oxygen and was monitored closely.  Her CellCept 250 mg twice daily was placed on hold due to her COVID infection.  Infectious Disease Service was consulted and they recommended Decadron if worsening oxygen requirements. She was able to wean off oxygen and did not have ambulatory desaturation when assessed by Pulmonary Rehab.    She had a slight trend down in WBC/ANC. This would be monitored as an outpatient and did not require Neupogen while hospitalized. She was eager to discharge home where she could support and be supported by her husband who has mild dementia. She has Tandem 365 as a steady resource and a home pulse oximeter. She agreed to return to the hospital if her symptoms worsened or if she had oxygen desaturation. She was sent home in stable condition on 11/2/21.

I would like to say that the beginning of my problem started with the first vaccine, with second it intensified tremendously  and now with a booster I am having exactly the  same thing. I started getting numbness in my face, mainly on my left side. Pins and needles and tingling. It would spread to my right side not as constant as with left side.  After the second vaccine it became so persistent  and disruptive . I told myself maybe it is from cold, from running, maybe it was dental issue. Once we started going back to doctors I eliminated all these things and with my primary physician we decided to do MRI of the brain. That came back ok and with the time my numbness never disappeared but it was not as constant or I perhaps learned to live with it.   I knew all along it must have been from the vaccine, the way it just started out of nowhere. Now that I got my third dose and  I am back at the beginning. Same sensation, same numbness, pins and needles on my left side of the face. Its again as constant as it was before.  I wanted to report it first time it started happening but than I figure maybe it was something else.  .

I realize the vaccine is for the Covid virus, and shouldn't have any effect on bacteria, but I'm wondering if my immune system is somehow more reactive to any sort of infection in my body?

Pt. consumed 16oz of water. 1:37PM, BP: 128/80, HR 68. Pt. states she feels better and wished to go home to eat. 1:40PM when asked, pt. refused EMS/further care and stated she wanted to stay home. Received the Moderna Vaccine.  Nurse called my name, I entered the room.  She stated you are here for your Booster.  I replied, No, I am here for my 3d dose.  She asked if that is what my Doctor wanted me to have and I replied yes.  She reached into a tray of many syringes.  Uncertain what dose I was about to receive I asked to see the syringe and at some point stated I was immunocompromised.  It was filled between a 2 and a 3 mark.  I went home and drew a picture of what I saw as I was uncertain if she gave me a Booster.  Then went to work.  Once home from work I learned that a full dose was .5 ml and a booster was .25 ml.  Called the pharmacist who seemed to think I did not know how to read a syringe.  I then went into the store at night and sheepishly asked to see the syringes and told the pharmacist that the nurse had written booster on my card and what I saw when I asked to look at the syringe.  He was annoyed and said we can write whatever we want on that card.  They are obviously overworked and burnt out.  I still don't know what I got though they insist it was a full dose.  Returned to the store on Monday and nurse corrected the card by adding .5 ml and her initials.

Patient received Sinovac for first and second dose in country, and presented today seeking a booster. Another pharmacist and I researched recommendations on booster for vaccines not approved in the country and found little info. We decided it was in the patient's best interest to adminster the Pfizer booster.

The first thing I saw was a very black bruise - it was at the site of the injection. I can still see the residue today from it. It is three or four inches wide and an inch and a half or two inches long - right now I can still see that. It was startling dark at the time - extreme bruise. I have not had that experience with injections in the past. A day or so later, after the bruise showed up, I had swelling - 3x3 inches below that injection bruise - it was swollen and had almost like a rash on it. It felt like it was warm as if it was a bee sting or spider bite. It was puffy and large and I couldn't sleep on it. It didn't go down for 5 days to a week. Even now, it's not real dark, but I can still see where it was. A person could look and see it. I did call the hospital and they told me to report it. Another thing that has happened, last week, probably on Wednesday, I called a dentist because I had so much swelling underneath my left jaw. I thought a tooth was infected. The dentist could not locate anything that is wrong but I do have crowns. She suggested that I have me ear and throat get checked out. I went to an Urgent Care and they found nothing. Underneath my jaw, I still have a little tenderness and that it still hadn't gone away. I called my doctor - and they said it could be related to vaccine but we don't know.
